<FIRST>r i PM-Siberiaks     04-03 1083</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Siberiaks,1113</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Siberian Deportees, A Chance To Come Into The Open</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The old people make their way in ones or
twos across the cobbled street, down the steps to the church
basement and the registration tables.
   There they pour out tearful, horrifying stories of brutal work
in freezing conditions, a daily ration of less than one pound of
watery bread, and relatives who did not make it back from the
wastelands of Siberia.
   The stories have been repeated thousands of times since January
as people register for membership in the newly legalized ``Union of
Siberiaks,'' Polish slang for people deported to Siberia _ or more
generally to the Soviet Union _ during the Stalinist era.
   ``Siberiaks'' are coming into the open after decades of silence
because of a changed political climate that permits them to speak
publicly about wrongs committed against them by Soviet secret
police and their Polish helpers.
   ``There are people who come now and say they spent eight years
there, 10 years, 14 years _ two or three times more than the entire
war. That is what so terrible about it,'' said Ryszard Reiff,
president of the association.
   ``If one travels for six weeks in a boxcar built for cattle,
during such travel out of 90 people locked up in a car, 20 died and
were thrown out .... Small children are freezing or suffocating in
the car. And then those tiny bodies are simply thrown out ....
   ``Can one ever forget a thing like this?''
   According to Reiff, about 1.5 million Poles were deported deep
into the Soviet Union between 1939 and the early 1950s.
   Most of the deportations came soon after the Soviets invaded
Poland from the east in September 1939 while Nazi Germany was
invading from the west. The two powers had secretly agreed to
partition Poland in the Ribbentrop-Molotov non-aggression pact of
August 1939.
   A smaller wave of deportations took place at the end of the war
when the Red Army won back control of Poland from the Nazis, and
the Soviet NKVD secret police arrived to sweep away any possible
resistance to communist control of postwar Poland.
   Of those deported, about 500,000 Poles died in the Soviet Union,
500,000 remained there or emigrated to other countries, and 500,000
eventually returned to Poland, Reiff said.
   Reiff said he was an underground resistance officer who was
caught by the Soviets in 1944 and sent away for two years until he
escaped and walked back to Poland. He remembers Siberia as a
``strange and terrible country.''
   ``There they care neither about space nor about time ....
Siberia is big, even the Soviet soldiers wore unhemmed coats. They
wore endless coats, like the endless land. And they didn't care
about time either. They would say `for five minutes' and it lasted
five years.''
   Reiff was asked to lead the Siberiaks by a group of about 20
people who won permission from communist authorities to organize
the union in December 1988. A former head of the Catholic political
group PAX, the 65-year-old journalist-politician is known in Poland
as the man who was removed from the Council of State after he was
the only member to protest martial law in 1981.
   Since the union's first meeting Jan. 13, 6,000 people have
registered in Warsaw alone, and a bigger group has formed in the
southwestern city of Wroclaw, said group spokesman Jerzy-Marek
Wlodarek. A nationwide membership count has not been completed.
   Some members have shocking accounts. One man reported being sent
to Siberia as late as 1953, when deportations of Poles were thought
to have ended. Another wrote claiming to have seen Polish officers
being taken to their executions by the NKVD, predecessor of the
KGB, at Katyn in 1940.
   Although the Polish government has begun to admit Soviet guilt
for the massacre of Polish officers at Katyn, and there have been
several pieces in the official press about Siberian deportations,
such topics remain very sensitive.
   Siberiaks seem to care little about eventual compensation for
pension and disability payments for these imprisonments. Their main
interest seems to be speaking loudly about the crimes against them
so that they are not forgotten.
   ``The truth finally comes out that not only Germans were killing
Poles, but somebody else was too,'' said one elderly woman at St.
Andrew's Church, moments after enrolling in the union.
   ``I was 10 years old and went to Siberia with my mother, brother
and sister. And before that, they arrested my father for having
volunteered in 1920 (to fight with Poland in a war against the
fledgling Soviet Union.)''
   Her father was put in a camp at Kotlas, she said. ``There were
thousands of Poles killed there. They were leading people into the
woods, and those people never came back. They were murdering them
there, like in Katyn.''
   Taken from her home near Bialystok in 1940, she did heavy labor
for four years until her release at age 14.
   White-haired Jadwiga Cieslicka came to the union in March
clutching a bound, typewritten manuscript and scrapbook by her late
husband, Kazimierz, recounting his fate and that of his fellow
villagers taken to Siberia.
   She opened it delicately to show a letter he wrote his mother on
a scrap of brown paper and photos of 21 men from his village who
had been arrested.
   ``This is the moment where it first sees daylight,'' said Mrs.
Cieslicka. ``Up to now, I could not show it to anybody. I want to
reveal everything my husband left, so it is not forgotten.''
   Her husband, who died two years ago, lived in Urzedow, a village
near Lublin in eastern Poland. He fought along with other men of
the village in the Home Army against the Germans.
   ``In '44, when the Soviets came in, he was taken away. And it
was totally unexpected because they thought they were fighting the
same enemy,'' she said.
   He and his brother were put to work as miners for two years.
``It was in Siberia where they have white bears and temperatures of
40 degrees below zero,'' she said with a shudder.
   Their son, Jaroslaw, a doctor, says conditions in Siberia
hastened his father's death.
   ``We can speak about it out loud now. It's wonderful that there
is this union,'' he said.
   ``It can't be forgotten, the people who did it, who killed our
fathers. They should be held responsible.''
</TEXT>
