<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionMarches     04-03 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Marches,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands March To Support Abortion Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 20,000 people marched in a show
of support for a woman's right to have an abortion, one of several
demonstrations held around the country.
   Sunday's ``March for Women's Lives,'' was timed to counter
demonstrations by anti-abortion groups like the New York
state-based Operation Rescue, whose members disrupt clinics
nationwide where abortions are performed.
   In New York City, about 400 abortion rights activists, some
hoisting giant clothes hangers, clashed with anti-abortionists in
front of St. Patrick's Cathedral. Nine activists were arrested.
   In Los Angeles, pro-choice demonstrators gathered at City Hall,
where they drew outlines of women's bodies on the ground and placed
red-stained clothes hangers inside each outline. And in Atlanta,
about 75 activists bearing the slogan ``we will not go back''
rallied at the Capitol.
   Both sides have been galvanized by a recent U.S. Supreme Court
decision to hear a case that could eventually overturn the court's
1973 Roe vs. Wade decision legalizing abortion.
   ``My mother had a choice. Will I?'' read a sign on a baby
carriage pushed by Jeanette Badal, 39, of Berkeley.
   ``I was able to make the choice because of Roe versus Wade. I
don't want anyone denied that choice,'' she said as she pushed her
9-month-old daughter.
   ``It's been my conviction but I hadn't actually come out and
marched before,'' added Carolyn Brady, 42, of Palo Alto. ``I just
think there's too much pressure from the other side, the
right-to-lifers. They're in the minority but they're getting much
more attention than they represent.''
   Margaret Connell, 59, of Santa Barbara, marched with her
85-year-old mother and 30-year-old daughter, carrying a sign that
said ``Three generations for choice.''
   The San Francisco march was sponsored by more than 100
organizations, including the National Organization for Women, the
Planned Parenthood Association and the American Civil Liberties
Union. It was held in conjunction with a scheduled April 9
``pro-choice'' rally in Washington, D.C.
</TEXT>
