<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Anti-Nuke     04-03 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Anti-Nuke,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say March Over Ecology Turns Violent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police clashed in the western city of
Poznan with hundreds of marchers protesting the planned
construction of a nuclear power plant, and the government said 17
policemen were injured.
   A spokesman for the Solidarity Information Service blamed police
for Sunday's violence, saying officers blocked exit routes from a
rally then beat several hundred marchers.
   ``SIS is of the opinion that the incident occurred as the result
of the attitude of police which made it impossible for
demonstrators to disperse peacefully,'' said Wojciech Maziarski, a
spokesman in Warsaw for the service, which publicizes information
on opposition activities.
   The state-run PAP news agency said, ``Groups of youths acting
under the slogan of protecting the environment committed hooligan
acts by throwing stones, screws and benches at law enforcement
forces.''
   Seventeen officers were injured, one had to be taken to a
hospital and five police vehicles were damaged, PAP said. It did
not report any arrests or injuries.
   Maziarski said about 2,000 people participated in the march
protesting plans to construct a nuclear power station at Klempicz,
a city of about 585,000 people about 30 miles northwest of Poznan.
   The plant, to be built by the year 2000, would be Poland's
second nuclear power station. The first is under construction in
Zarnowiec on the Baltic coast, and is to be finished in two years.
   After attending a Mass in Poznan, the protesters marched to the
town square but could not leave for two hours because of police
blockades, Maziarski said.
   Maziarski said police beat marchers who tried to exit by one
street, then announced that the protesters could leave by another
street. When the marchers went to that street it too was blocked
and police used batons, tear gas and water cannon on the marchers,
he said.
   Maziarski said police later lifted the cordons.
