<FIRST>r a PM-DoctorKilled     04-03 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doctor Killed,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Arrested for Killing Doctor Shows No Remorse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man accused of strangling a pregnant
pathologist at a New York City hospital says he felt no sympathy
for the doctor.
   Steven Smith, 23, said in three recent telephone interviews with
The State newspaper that Dr. Kathryn Hinnant's slaying Jan. 7
received an inordinate amount of media attention because she was
white and middle class.
   The interviews were conducted while Smith, who is black and used
to sleep in a storage area at Bellevue Hospital, was in the Rikers
Island prison and at a pretrial holding facility, the newspaper
reported today. He has since been transferred to a psychiatric unit
in Brooklyn.
   Hinnant, a 33-year-old native of Lake City, was beaten, raped,
strangled and robbed. Smith was arrested Jan. 9. He said he robbed
the doctor but maintains he is innocent of the other charges.
   When asked if he sympathized with Hinnant, who was five months
pregnant, Smith sharply responded that he did not and began
speaking of his slain sister.
   ``It ain't nothing new to me,'' said Smith, who said he had sold
crack and robbed people since he was 16. ``When my sister died, she
wasn't even in the news.''
   His sister, Diane Eunice Flowers, was shot to death at her New
London, Conn., home in 1980, when Smith was 16. Police said it was
an accident.
   A New York judge is considering whether statements Smith gave to
police are admissible in court, and prosecutors are awaiting
results of a genetic test that could link Smith to the sexual
assault.
</TEXT>
