<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1012EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Mother     04-03 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Mother,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Hear Child Protection, Parental Rights Dispute in Maryland
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether a Maryland mother may be jailed for refusing to reveal the
whereabouts of her son, who authorities fear may be dead.
   The justices said they will hear arguments by prosecutors who
say the need to protect abused children in such cases outweighs a
parent's constitutional right against self-incrimination.
   The court also granted an appeal filed in behalf of the woman's
son.
   The case dates back to Jan. 23, 1987, when Jacqueline
Bouknight's three-month-old son Maurice was admitted to a Baltimore
hospital with a broken leg and other partially healed fractures.
   Suspecting the infant had been abused, Baltimore social workers
put Maurice in foster care and later obtained a court order giving
the city protective custody of him.
   City officials also said Ms. Bouknight suffered from emotional
problems and had been observed throwing Maurice into his crib
during the infant's hospitalization. Ms. Bouknight did not dispute
the city's assertions.
   Maurice was returned to Ms. Bouknight's custody on July 17,
1987, after she agreed not to punish him physically and to undergo
training in acquiring parenting skills.
   But nine months later, the social workers said Ms. Bouknight no
longer was cooperating with them. They said Maurice's father
recently had been shot to death, and that Ms. Bouknight was using
drugs.
   They also said they feared Maurice might be dead.
   Ms. Bouknight was held in contempt by a judge on April 28, 1988,
after she refused to disclose Maurice's whereabouts. The day before
she told the judge the boy was with her sister in Texas, but the
sister said she had not seen Maurice.
   The judge ordered Ms. Bouknight jailed until she revealed where
her son is.
   The Maryland Court of Appeals, by a 5-2 vote last Dec. 19, ruled
that jailing Ms. Bouknight for refusing to disclose information
about her son's whereabouts violated her constitutional protection
against self-incrimination.
   The state court said, ``In these circumstances, if the
information discloses that Maurice is now dead, or has been subject
to criminal abuse, as the prosecution candidly fears, suspicion
concededly would focus on Bouknight as the criminal agent.
   ``By disclosing the demanded information, therefore, Bouknight
would, in the event a crime had been committed upon Maurice's
person, be incriminating herself.''
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist set aside the state court
decision pending further review of the case by the full Supreme
Court. He thus reinstated the contempt citation and the indefinite
jailing of Ms. Bouknight.
   In any event, prosecutors said she was behind bars on
independent grounds _ a theft conviction that resulted in an
18-month jail sentence.
   Advocates for Children and Youth in Baltimore joined Maryland
officials in urging the justices to reverse the state court's
ruling that Ms. Bouknight's constitutional rights were violated.
   The children's rights organization said the state court ruling
could tie the hands of juvenile courts in protecting neglected and
abused children.
   The cases are Baltimore Department of Social Services vs.
Bouknight, 88-1182, and Maurice M. vs. Bouknight, 88-6651.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890403-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1015EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Helmsleys     04-03 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Helmsleys,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Refuses to Dismiss Helmsley Indictment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to throw out
an indictment accusing New York City hotel owners Harry and Leona
Helmsley of federal income tax evasion.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that dismissed
the Helmsleys' challenge to the 47-count indictment.
   Today's action comes less than a week after the high court, in
an unrelated case, limited the right of criminal defendants to
challenge indictments before trial.
   The justices on March 28 ruled that federal criminal defendants
who fail to persuade a judge to throw out their indictments because
of alleged misconduct by prosecutors cannot appeal before they are
tried and convicted.
   The Helmsleys' appeal raised the same issue.
   They were indicted with two hotel executives a year ago on
charges they evaded some $1.2 million in federal taxes over a
three-year period.
   The Helmsleys said the indictment should be thrown out because
of pre-indictment publicity generated by federal prosecutors.
   On numerous occasions, the Helmsleys contended, unnamed law
enforcement officials were quoted in news articles making accusing
and unflattering comments about the hotel owners.
   For example, one newspaper article that appeared two weeks
before the indictment quoted an anonymous investigator as saying
``people were waiting in line to testify against'' Mrs. Helmsley.
   A federal judge who refused to throw out the indictment said
there was no persuasive evidence that the grand jury was influenced
by the news coverage.
   The case is Helmsley vs. U.S., 88-732.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
