<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Boeing     04-03 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Boeing,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Accepts Contractor-Severence Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether defense contractors violate a federal conflict-of-interest
law when paying severance to employees who quit to take important
government jobs.
   The court said it will hear appeals by the Boeing Co. and five
former employees who received $485,000 in severance when they left
to take jobs in the Reagan administration.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last May ordered either
Boeing or the former employees to turn the severance payments over
to the government.
   The appeals court said Boeing paid the money to the employees to
compensate them for taking lower-paying government jobs.
   Such payments create at least the appearance of a conflict of
interest, the appeals court said.
   ``We hold that payments made to future federal employees before
they begin government service can violate (federal
conflict-of-interest law) if they are made with compensatory
intent,'' the appeals court said.
   Government lawyers urged the Supreme Court to reject the appeals
by Boeing and the five former employees.
   The government said the severance payments ``were classic
violations'' of federal law because ``they were intended to
encourage the recipients to accept (the government) positions and
they were calculated to supplement the recipients' federal salaries
by making up the difference between their government pay and their
higher pay with Boeing.''
   The five are Thomas K. Jones, who received $132,000 from Boeing
before he became deputy under-secretary of defense for strategic
and theater nuclear forces in 1981; Herbert A. Reynolds, $80,000,
deputy director of space and intelligence policy in 1981; Melvin R.
Paisley, $183,000, assistant secretary of the Navy for research,
engineering and systems in 1981; Lawrence H. Crandon, $40,000, a
computer scientist for the NATO air command and control systems in
1982; and Harold Kitson, $50,000, deputy assistant secretary of the
Navy for command, communications and control intelligence in 1982.
   The former employees, in the appeal acted on today, said they
were not responsible for Pentagon contracting or procurement, and
said they had exemplary records with the government.
   They argued there was no question of divided loyalties for any
of them because each ``received an irrevocable severance payment
... before he entered into government service.''
   The cases are Crandon vs. U.S., 88-931; Boeing vs. U.S., 88-938.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
