<HEAD>Eds: Subs Jackson-dated 4th item to add comments from Welty, Roger
Mudd afte 3rd graf pvs, picking up last graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Eudora Welty received a standing
ovation at a Mississippi Symphony Orchestra gala marking her 80th
birthday.
   In addition to ``Happy Birthday,'' the symphony on Sunday
performed a concerto that was commissioned especially for the
occasion.
   The idea to honor the author with ``Concerto for Orchestra:
Images From Welty'' came from conductor Colman Pearce.
   Between pieces, public television newsman Roger Mudd delivered a
tribute to Welty, whom he called ``a generous friend'' and ``very
hard not to like.''
   ``I have never heard Eudora say, `What I meant to say was ... '
I have never known Eudora to squander or trifle with God's great
gifts to her,'' Mudd said.
   ``I felt like ... I was close to tears the whole time,'' Welty
said afterward. ``And Roger, his was an expression of friendship
and I valued it enormously.''
   Welty, whose birthday is April 13, won the Pulitzer Prize in
1973 for her book, ``The Optimist's Daughter.'' Her
autobiographical ``One Writer's Beginnings'' is among her
best-known works.
