<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-NuclearDrugTests     04-03 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Nuclear Drug Tests,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Widespread Testing in Nuclear Industry Left Intact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today left intact a ruling
that permits widespread drug testing of workers in the nuclear
power industry.
   The court, without comment, turned away an appeal by workers
applying for jobs with a company that does maintenance work on a
nuclear plant in Washington state.
   The justices last month handed down their first drug-testing
decisions _ upholding drug and alcohol tests for railway workers
involved in accidents and for U.S. Customs Service employees
applying for drug enforcement jobs or jobs that require carrying a
firearm.
   The Washington Supreme Court last July upheld a mandatory
urine-testing program for applicants at Bechtel Construction Inc.
The company does repair and maintenance work during nuclear plant
shutdowns for the Washington Public Power Supply System (WPPSS).
   A group of plumbers, pipefitters and welders said the tests
violate privacy safeguards in the state and federal Constitutions.
   The state court threw out the state constitutional claim on
grounds it is pre-empted by federal law regulating nuclear power
plants.
   The state court also said that the tests do not violate the
federal Constitution because the nuclear industry is so heavily
regulated, and that those working in the industry have a reduced
expectationof privacy.
   ``The lingering effects of drug abuse can impair one's physical
and mental capacity, and such impairment can have catastrophic
consequences in the setting of a nuclear power facility,'' the
state court said.
   It added that testing applicants for such jobs is the only
opportunity the employer will have to determine whether a
prospective worker is using drugs. Unlike workers already on the
job, there is no opportunity to observe a job applicant, the state
court said.
   WPPSS does not test those already employed, unless there is
reason to suspect a worker is using drugs.
   ``Routine drug testing in the context of pre-employment
screening is virtually the only way in which the operators of the
WPPSS facility can effectively monitor compliance'' with rules
against drug use, the state court said.
   It noted that those who test positive are not prosecuted for
drug use and may reapply for employment six months later.
   ``There is no permanent stain on an applicant's record,'' the
state court said.
   The case is Alverado vs. WPPSS, 88-645.
</TEXT>
