<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-MartinMarietta     04-03 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Martin Marietta,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Lawyer Confidentiality Dispute in Maryland Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today turned away a dispute
over the confidentiality of lawyers' documents in a case stemming
from a defense contractor's fraudulent travel reimbursement scheme.
   The court, without comment, refused to hear appeals by Martin
Marietta Corp. and a former employee who said the company is trying
to make him the scapegoat for the scheme.
   Martin Marietta, based in Bethesda, Md., pleaded guilty in 1987
to mail fraud and furnishing the government with a false statement.
The company was fined $12,000 and ordered to repay $250,000 the
government spent investigating the case.
   Martin Marietta also paid the government more than $4.3 million
in a separate non-criminal settlement with the Pentagon's
procurement arm, the Defense Logistics Agency.
   Federal investigators said a Martin Marietta subsidiary and a
travel agency it hired billed the government for the full price of
air fare when Martin Marietta employees traveled in connection with
Pentagon contracts.
   The investigators said the employees actually used discount
fares and received rebates that Martin Marietta kept for itself.
   While under investigation, Martin Marietta's lawyers turned over
various documents to federal prosecutors in an attempt to persuade
the government not to seek an indictment.
   The case acted on today involves an effort by indicted former
Martin Marietta employee William Pollard to obtain those records.
   Pollard headed a subsidiary the company set up to handle travel
arrangements for its workers.
   He was indicted on April 7, 1987, by a federal grand jury in
Baltimore on fraud charges.
   Pollard said he sought the records of the company lawyers to
help him prove that Martin Marietta is trying to make him the
scapegoat for the travel-rebate scheme.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last September ruled
partly in his favor and partly for the company.
   The appeals court ordered Martin Marietta to turn over a
substantial portion of the documents, including internal audits and
lawyers' memos. The appeals court said the usual secrecy protection
for exchanges between lawyers and clients was surrendered when the
Martin Marietta attorneys agreed to provide the documents to
federal prosecutors.
   But the appeals court said Pollard is not entitled to see
material in those memos and related documents in which lawyers
discuss theories of the case or give their impressions of such
matters as the credibility of witnesses.
   ``What should not be ordered to be disclosed (to Pollard) are
pure expressions of legal theory or metal impressions,'' the
appeals court said.
   Martin Marietta asked the Supreme Court to bar Pollard from
seeing any of the lawyers' memos.
   The company was supported by the American Bar Association, which
said the 4th Circuit court ruling compromises lawyer-client
confidentiality and jeopardizes efforts by suspects' lawyers to
cooperate with the government.
   Pollard, in a separate appeal, asked the high court to let him
see the uncensored versions of the memos, including the opinions
and impressions of the attorneys.
   The cases are Martin Marietta vs. Pollard, 88-1157, and Pollard
vs. Martin Marietta, 88-1338.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
