<DOCNO> AP890403-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1037EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Hispanics     04-03 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Hispanics,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justices Rule Texas Policy Doesn't Discriminate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ruled that a Texas
school board's policy does not violate the voting rights of
Hispanics.
   The court, by a 7-2 vote, upheld a policy limiting the power of
a single board member to place an item on the agenda for board
meetings.
   Justices Byron R. White and Antonin Scalia dissented, saying the
court should hear oral arguments in the case before deciding it.
   The school board in Victoria, Texas, has seven members. Since
1984, five board members have been elected from single-member
districts and two in at-large voting.
   Theresa Gutierrez became the first and only Mexican-American
elected to the school board in 1985. She represents a district with
a 51.4 percent Hispanic population and a 14 percent black
population.
   The school board in 1987 changed its policy for placing items on
meeting agendas. The new policy says the school board president may
require the approval of two board members _ also called trustees _
before an item can be added to the agenda for an upcoming meeting.
   Mrs. Gutierrez and others in her district said the new policy
affects the rights of voters she represents by reducing her power
to recommend agenda items.
   She said the federal Voting Rights Act requires that the U.S.
attorney general approve the policy before it can be implemented.
   But a three-judge federal court last year ruled against Ms.
Gutierrez and her constitutents.
   The federal court said the new policy's ``effect on the powers
of the elected trustees was at most minuscule.''
   The three-judge court compared the policy to the standard
parliamentary procedure that requires someone to second any motion
or resolution before it can be submitted to a vote.
   ``It seems plain to us that if Mrs. Gutierrez is unable to
persuade even one other trustee to join her in placing a matter on
the board's agenda, she would have no better succeess in procuring
a second should she have moved it at a meeting,'' the federal court
said.
   Also, the federal court said the policy ``in no way singles her
out for unfavorable procedural treatment.''
   The case is Rojas vs. Victoria Independent School District,
87-2118.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890403-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1040EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Casino     04-03 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Casino,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Revive Lawsuit by Penthouse Against Atlantic City
Casino</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to revive a
lawsuit by Penthouse International stemming from its failure to get
financing for an Atlantic City, N.J., casino.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that threw out a
$128.7 million judgment Penthouse won against a Virginia savings
and loan company and a Washington law firm.
   The court also rejected a related appeal by the savings and loan
company.
   Penthouse and its president, Robert Guccione, had invested some
$70 million in the proposed hotel and casino by June 1983 when the
company decided to seek outside financing to complete the project.
   Dominion Federal Savings &amp; Loan Association of McLean, Va.,
agreed to provide $35 million as part of a lending syndicate.
Dominion Federal retained the Washington law firm of Melrod, Redman
&amp; Gartlan to represent it in the negotiations.
   The savings and loan association pulled out of the deal in 1984,
and Penthouse then filed a federal suit in New York City accusing
the lending institution and the law firm of illegally breaking a
contract.
   A federal judge ruled for Penthouse, awarding it $128.7 million
in anticipated lost profits from the casino. The judge also ordered
Dominion Federal to pay another $7.7 million to Queen City Savings
&amp; Loan Association, which tried to arrange the casino financing.
   Both awards were thrown out last August by the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals.
   The appeals court said Dominion Federal and its law firm did not
act illegally in backing out of the deal.
   The appeals court also threw out a counterclaim by Dominion
Federal against Queen City.
   In the appeal acted on today, Penthouse lawyers said the appeals
court ruling ``fashions a rule of law for commercial transactions
completely at odds with the law of the state of New Jersey, which
the court had a duty to apply in this case.''
   The cases are Penthouse vs. Dominion Federal, 88-1144, and
Dominion Federal vs. Penthouse, 88-1339.
</TEXT>
