<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Wolfson     04-03 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Wolfson,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Turns Back Challenge to Conviction of Fortas' Friend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today turned away an appeal
by financier Louis Wolfson, a key figure in the scandal-marred
ending of the late Abe Fortas' career on the nation's highest court.
   The justices, without comment, let stand rulings that Wolfson
properly was convicted in 1967 of selling unregistered securities.
   Wolfson's appeal had sought to have his conviction overturned,
arguing that only expansive judicial interpretations of federal
securities law rendered his conduct illegal.
   Fortas, a brilliant Washington lawyer appointed to the Supreme
Court in 1965, resigned in 1969 following a disclosure that he had
agreed to accept a $20,000 annual fee from a foundation headed by
Wolfson.
   Fortas served as one of President Johnson's closest advisers
before, and at times after, his appointment to the nation's highest
court.
   During his court tenure, he was a staunch member of the liberal
wing headed by then-Chief Justice Earl Warren.
   Although denying any wrongdoing in accepting the Wolfson-led
foundation's fee, Fortas resigned under the threat of impeachment.
   He conceded that the fee was intended to be the first of a
series of annual $20,000 payments for the rest of his life _ and,
in the event of his death, for the life of his wife _ for
``continuing services'' to the foundation.
   At the time of the disclosure, Wolfson was serving a one-year
prison sentence on the securities law conviction.
   The case is Wolfson vs. U.S., 88-1422.
</TEXT>
