<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-BusAttendant     04-03 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Bus Attendant,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reconsideration of Ruling Ordered in District of Columbia Drug-Testing
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ordered
reconsideration of a ruling that allows District of Columbia
officials to require drug testing for employees involved in the
busing of handicapped students.
   The justices said a federal appeals court should re-examine the
case in light of their rulings last month on mandatory drug tests.
   The justices on March 21 announced their first drug-testing
decisions _ upholding drug and alcohol tests for railway workers
involved in accidents and U.S. Customs Service employees applying
for drug enforcement jobs or those jobs that require carrying a
firearm.
   The District of Columbia case stems from the firing _ and later
reinstatement _ of Juanita M. Jones, an attendant on a bus used to
transport handicapped students between their homes and schools.
   Ms. Jones was fired after testing positive for marijuana, and
was ordered reinstated by a federal judge who said she could not be
fired on the basis of the drug test conducted by the city because
of its questionable reliability in determining on-the-job drug use.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here ruled in 1987 that the
city government generally may require workers in such jobs to
undergo routine testing for drugs because they are responsibile for
the safety of schoolchildren.
   But the appeals court ruling did not alter the judge's decision
reinstating Ms. Jones. That sparked a Supreme Court appeal by
school district officials.
   Justice John Paul Stevens dissented from the high court's order
today. He said the school district's appeal should be turned down.
   The case is McKenzie vs. Jones, 87-1706.
</TEXT>
