<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1944EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-EarlPromotion     04-03 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earl Promotion,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Col. Robert Earl, rebuffed by the Senate
for promotion last year because of questions about his role in the
Iran-Contra affair, failed this year to win nomination for
advancement from the Marine Corps, officials said Monday.
   Earl, 43, served as the deputy to Lt. Col. Oliver North on the
staff of the National Security Council from February 1986 to
January 1987. North is on trial in U.S. District Court here,
accused of concealing from Congress and former Attorney General
Edwin Meese III his efforts on behalf of the Nicaraguan Contra
guerillas.
   Earl, now a plans officer at the Marine Corps Combat Development
Command in Quantico, Va., has acknowledged that he was aware of the
diversion of profits from arms sales to Iran to support the
Contras, and said that he aided North in the destruction of records
after the affair became public.
   Last fall, a Marine Corps promotion board selected Earl for
advancement to the rank of colonel. The Senate Armed Services
Committee, however, took the unusual step of refusing the promotion
while allowing others on the Marine list to go forward.
   At the time, Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the chairman of the panel,
said he was troubled that the corps apparently had not considered
Earl's activities at the White House when it reviewed his military
record.
   Monday, Maj. Ron Stokes, a spokesman for the corps, said that a
list of 130 Marine lieutenant colonels selected for advancement to
colonel had been sent to the Senate two weeks ago and that Earl's
name was not on the list.
   The spokesman said Navy Secretary William L. Ball III had
ordered a special three-member board of generals to study the
matter after the Senate panel's rebuff last year. The generals
later submitted a report recommending that certain Iran-Contra
activities by Earl be included in his military personnel records,
the spokesman continued.
   ``Secretary Ball approved, and Lt. Col. Earl then had an
opportunity to review the report and respond in writing to the
recommendations, which he did,'' said Stokes.
   ``Then the whole package was sent to the selection board. But he
wasn't selected by this board, that's true.''
   Earl testified last week at North's trial under a grant of
immunity, which he received in exchange for the testimony he had
given Congress. Earl said through a spokesman that he would not
comment on the promotion board's decision.
   Earl, a graduate of the U.S. Naval Academy, is a 22-year Marine
Corps veteran. He is not required to retire and remains eligible
for promotion each year. His rejection by the board this year,
however, reduces his chances for next year.
   Besides Earl, the Senate last year also rebuffed the selection
of Army Col. James Steele to become a brigadier general. Steele is
the former head of the U.S. Military Assistance Group in El
Salvador and played a role in the secret Contra resupply operation.
   The Army has not decided whether to again recommend Steele for
promotion, Lt. Col. Greg Rixon, a spokesman, said Monday.
</TEXT>
