<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1945EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Education     04-03 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Education,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Seeking Congressional Co-Sponsors for Education Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is seeking House and
Senate co-sponsors for a $422 million education bill containing the
president's proposals for merit schools, magnet schools and other
education programs.
   The Educational Excellence Act of 1989 is scheduled for
introduction Wednesday by Sen. Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., and Rep.
Bill Goodling, R-Pa., according to a sponsor-recruitment letter
circulating on Capitol Hill.
   The programs in the bill are the same ones President Bush
proposed in his budget message to Congress. Administration
officials have said they don't know whether the new spending would
be offset by cuts in other education programs or added to the
Education Department budget submitted by then-President Reagan.
   The bulk of the money in the Bush bill, $250 million, would go
for a ``Presidential Merit Schools'' program of cash awards to
public and private elementary schools that have made substantial
progress in raising student educational achievement, creating a
safe and drug-free environment, and reducing the dropout rate.
   Another $100 million would create a new ``magnet schools of
excellence'' program to set up or enhance magnet schools to
strengthen academic and vocational offerings as well as promote
open enrollment and parental choice. Bush's program would be
separate from an existing magnet schools program designed to
achieve desegregation.
   Bush is also proposing $25 million apiece for programs of
emergency grants to urban schools with the nation's most severe
drug problems and grants to states to develop alternative ways to
certify teachers and principals.
   He is seeking $10 million to use as challenge grants for
endowments at historically black colleges and universities and $7.6
million for ``president's awards for excellence in education'' to
outstanding teachers. Another $5 million would go for scholarships
to high school seniors with top grades in science and math under a
``national science scholars program.''
   In a draft message to Congress, circulating along with the bill,
Bush said the plan rewards excellence; directs federal dollars to
those most in need; gives parents and school systems greater
flexibility and choice; and increases accountability by measuring
and rewarding progress toward quality education.
   Congressional response to Bush's proposals has been mixed.
Several lawmakers, including House Education and Labor Committee
Chairman Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., have said the administration
plan gives short shrift to effective existing programs and have
offered alternative education spending blueprints of their own.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
