<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 2003EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SkiSeason     04-03 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ski Season,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vermont Ski Season Third Best, Despite Lack Of Snow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lack of snow didn't stop Vermont from a
good ski season, it's third best, because resorts were able to rely
heavily on fake stuff.
   The Vermont Ski Areas Association estimates skier day visits at
4.2 million, down from 4.85 million last season.
   The best season on record was 1986-87, when 5.2 million skier
days were recorded.
   Business was good at some of the smaller resorts, which spent
considerable money on snowmaking and advertising before the season
began. Okemo Mountain, which advertises heavily in the New York
area, said business was up 3-5 percent.
   Resorts in the north also seemed to fare well, thanks to heavier
snowfall. Jay Peak reported a 16 percent increase in business and
Burke Mountain an 8 percent increase, the VSAA said.
   But Killington was down 4 percent and Mount Snow also reported a
drop in skier visits, said Candace Moot, VSAA associate director.
   ``Killington is a large percentage of the market, and Mount
Snow, too. They brought the statewide average down,'' she said.
   Business was also down at smaller, family-owned operations like
Cochran Ski Area in Richmond.
   ``People didn't think skiing,'' said co-owner Virginia Cochran,
whose area has 30 percent snowmaking. ``I also think it was a nice
winter to be outdoors. Kids could ride their bikes all winter or
play basketball in the driveway, or they could go hiking.''
   Many of the resorts will likely close this month. Ascutney
Mountain, Burke, Suicide Six, Maple Valley, Haystack and the
Middlebury College Snow Bowl have already closed, while Bromley and
Magic Mountains are only open on weekends.
   Killington, Mount Snow and Stratton normally try to stay open
through May.
</TEXT>
