<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1643EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HousingAffordability 1stLd-Writethru a0586 04-03 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Affordability, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0586,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Affordability Measure Down Sharply in February</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs first 2 grafs with Realtors' CORRECTION that drop was sharpest
in 15 years, instead of sharpest drop ever</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An index measuring the ability of the typical
American family to buy a home made its sharpest drop in 15 years
last month, as rising mortgage rates and home prices resulted in a
loss of purchasing power, a real estate trade group said Monday.
   The National Association of Realtors said its affordability
index was at 105 in February, down 5.1 index points from a revised
110.1 in January. It was the biggest month-to-month decline since
the measure dropped 5.2 index points from 137 to 131.8 in January
1974.
   February's index level meant that a family earning the median
income of $32,314 annually had 5 percent more income than needed to
qualify for a mortgage covering 80 percent of the purchase price of
a median-priced home.
   The median price for an existing home in February was $93,100,
meaning half the homes sold for more and half for less. February's
median price was up $3,400 from January.
   The mortgage rate used to calculate the index rose to 9.77
percent in February from 9.61 percent, representing a composite of
fixed and adjustable rates.
   John A. Tuccillo, chief economist for the Realtors, said the
index was likely to decline again in March, since mortgage rates
continued to increase, although prices and rates should level off
later this spring.
   The affordability index has been above 100 since it hit 99.8 in
May 1986.
   ``For nearly three years, housing affordability for the typical
buyer has been well above the break-even point,'' said Ira Gribin,
president of the Realtors group. ``But hikes in mortgage rates and
prices have made buying more difficult.''
</TEXT>
