<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-ShipAground     04-03 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Ship Aground,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Tanker Runs Aground In Rhine, Spill Averted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WIESBADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvage crews on Monday towed a
badly damaged oil tanker into port after it ran aground in the
Rhine River, and officials said any danger of a major oil spill was
over.
   Workers pumped about 42,000 gallons of fuel oil out of the
vessel Rhinetank 24 and towed it to Oppenheim harbor, where the
rest of the load was being pumped out, said the Hesse state Water
Protection Police.
   The ship was originally carrying about 300,000 gallons of fuel
oil.
   Officials had been worried the vessel could break apart because
of the strong Rhine currents and spill its cargo into the river,
but the police said that danger had passed now that the ship was in
the protected harbor.
   The vessel ran aground on an underwater stone wall near the city
of Oppenheim, about 25 miles southwest of Frankfurt, early Monday,
according to the Water Protection Police.
   The ship later dislodged from the wall but was badly damaged.
   Small amounts of fuel oil spilled into the Rhine, and shipping
was backed up for several hours as crews pumped oil out of the
crippled 300-foot tanker in preparation for towing it to port.
   Water protection authorities surrounded the stricken vessel with
oil containment booms and transferred some of the oil from the
damaged tanker to another ship, said Jochen Boehm, a spokesman for
the Water Protection Office in Mainz.
   He said one of the ship's 12 oil storage containers was damaged
and initially leaked small amounts of the ship's cargo, but that
the oil was quickly cleaned up by salvage crews.
   Boehm said he did not know the size of the leak or whether there
had been any environmental damage.
   More than 100 ships had to wait for several hours as workers
pumped oil out of the crippled tanker. The shipping lane at
Oppenheim was reopened in late afternoon.

</TEXT>
