<FIRST>r a AM-ChessDefection     04-03 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chess Defection,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gata Kamsky Makes First Appearance Since Defection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet chess prodigy Gata Kamsky said Monday
that he and his father defected to the United States because Soviet
chess officials had blocked his career for the last three years.
   ``I decided to leave the Soviet Union because I can't play in
chess tournaments, so I can't grow in chess. Here I can play in all
the tournaments every year,'' the 14-year-old Kamsky, speaking in
English, said at a crowded news conference at the Marshall Chess
Club in Greenwich Village.
   His father, Rustam Kamsky, reading from a statement in faltering
English, said: ``Now we get the freedom. My son can play in
different cities in all the world. Please help my wife.''
   Rustam said his wife, Bella, who is Gata's stepmother and
remains in Leningrad, knew in advance of their decision to request
asylum in the United States when they came here for a chess
tournament three weeks ago.
   ``Yes, they discussed it, all together as a family, and they
jointly came to this decision that they would stay here,'' said Lev
Albert, a grandmaster who defected from the Soviet Union in 1979
and translated for the Kamskys.
   Rustam Kamsky said discrimination against the family because
they were ethnic Crimean Tatars also had some bearing on their
decision.
   ``Tatars don't have their homeland. ... Moscow is like an
occupying power,'' he said. ``Organizers in the other republics are
able to support their players. But because there is no such thing
for the Tatars, they are in an underprivileged position compared
with other chess players.''
   As they fielded questions, the defectors fiddled with a
miniature of the Statue of Liberty, which stood on a table in front
of Gata. Asked if he knew what it was, Gata replied, ``It's the
Statue of Liberty. The symbol of America, the symbol of freedom.''
   Using a term first employed by world champion Garri Kasparov for
the Soviet chess establishment, Gata said, ``In Soviet Union, I
can't do anything with the mafia.'' The elder Kamsky said Soviet
officials had limited his son's opportunities to play. ``Garri
Kasparov was trying to fight against this group which controls
Soviet chess, but even Kasparov is often unsuccessful,'' he said.
   Kamsky said their position was far weaker than Kasparov's and in
the end they decided, ``We couldn't do anything here.''
   Last Tuesday, the young Kamsky, who experts predict will reach
the highest echelons of world chess, and his father asked for
political asylum in the United States before the last round of the
New York Open tournament.
   Kamsky won his final round game and was spirited away to an
undisclosed address in Princeton, N.J., where the Kamskys have been
staying with James Sherwin, the president of the American Chess
Foundation.
   Later this week, they are expected to move into their own
apartment, probably in the Russian-speaking neighborhood of
Brighton Beach in Brooklyn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
