<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     04-03 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unmarked Graves Will be Investigated, Attorney General Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unmarked graves that may contain
victims of political repression by the deposed regime of Gen.
Alfredo Stroessner will be investigated, the attorney general said
Monday.
   In a separate development, provisional president Andres
Rodriguez extended voter registration by another 10 days for the
May 1 elections, and said indelible ink would be used on voters'
hands to prevent multiple voting. Both were concessions to
opposition demands.
   On Saturday, human rights activist Francisco de Vargas excavated
what he said may be one of 30 graves on a river bank near Colonia
Esperanza, 90 miles east of Asuncion. He said residents told him
they saw police execute victims near the grave site.
   The grave contained shards of bone, false teeth and a skull with
possibly a bullet hole through it, he said.
   ``We view this finding with concern and will put all our effort
into gathering enough information to begin a formal
investigation,'' said Attorney General Diogenes Martinez.
   Three Asuncion police officers accused of torturing prisoners
during the Stroessner regime have been suspended from duty.
   Rodriguez, also the army commander, pledged to respect human
rights and uphold civil liberties shortly after he toppled
Stroessner in a Feb. 3 coup.
   Rodriguez this weekend formally accepted the nomination as
ruling Colorado Party candidate in the May presidential elections.
He is widely expected to win.
   On Monday, he said he extended voter registration so that ``the
largest amount of people possible can vote in upcoming elections,
and that they will be considered clean.''
   Indelible ink will be used during balloting ``so there really
will be no possibility of fraud, and each person can deposit only
one vote,'' he said.
   Both measures were requested by opposition political parties.
   They also demanded Rodriguez support a constitutional reform and
agree not to seek re-election in 1993 if he wins May 1. Rodriguez
endorsed the latter two requests on Sunday.
