<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Tax     04-03 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Tax,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Queries on Consumer Tax Keep Government Busy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government workers have been busy answering
questions or listening to complaints on a controversial new tax
reform that features a 3 percent sales levy, an official said
Monday.
   The Fair Trade Commission has received more than 300 phone calls
from Tokyo residents about the reform, which was implemented
Saturday, said commission spokesman Eiichiro Kokubo.
   Most callers to the ``cartel emergency line'' pointed out
unwarranted price markups, and expressed fears of inflation, he
said.
   Japan's first tax reform since World War II covers everything
from taxi rides to apartment rents. It offsets cuts in corporate,
inheritance, higher-level income and residential taxes by $44.6
billion in fiscal 1989 with the sales tax, designed to gather $24
billion in this first year.
   Under the reform, the government adjusted a variety of taxes
unevenenly, befuddling consumers.
   For example, the price of expensive imported liquor fell, while
milk prices rose and the price of soft drinks sold in vending
machines stayed the same. Television sets were cheaper, but
newspapers raised their prices.
   The government granted a special exemption for small businesses,
who were not required to collect the 3 percent sales tax on goods
and services. Small business and agriculture are the political
mainstay of the government, led by Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
   But many exempt enterprises such as taxis and discount stores,
raised prices anyway. Some, to offset increased operating costs,
others simply for profit.
   The commission's telephone advisory service will continue for
two years as the government looks for abuses in the new system,
Kokubo said.
   The Economic Planning Agency has also received about 760 phone
calls and consumer unions nationwide about 400 queries since
Saturday, agency spokeswoman Mitsuko Asada said.
   The tax reform and a stock-profiteering scandal involving
Takeshita and many party members have led to support ratings as low
as 9 percent in recent opinion polls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
