<FIRST>r w AM-ValdezVisit     04-03 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Valdez Visit,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Visit to Spill Upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House subcommittee with
jurisdiction over the Alaska pipeline will fly to Alaska on Tuesday
to examine the damage caused by the oil spill in Prince William
Sound, congressional aides said Monday.
   Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., whose Interior subcommittee on
water, power and offshore energy resources will be considering
legislation that would allow exploration for more oil on Alaska's
North Slope, said the spill could change congressional attitudes
about future drilling.
   ``The oil spill has raised many serious questions about the
ability of the industry to safely operate in a fragile
environmental area,'' said Miller.
   ``I plan to witness first hand the impact of the spill and to
investigate its possible implications for future oil development in
Alaska and for U.S. energy policy in general.''
   Miller's office said a staff attorney has been collecting
confidential information in Alaska since March 29. The spill
occurred March 24 when the oil tanker Exxon Valdez ran aground,
dumping 10 million gallons of oil into the sound.
   Miller, the attorney and Miller's subcommittee staff director
will tour the port at Valdez and Cordova, the fishing hub in
eastern Prince William Sound.
   They also will meet with representatives from Exxon, the Alyeska
Pipeline Co., local fishermen, the state Department of
Environmental Conservation, the Coast Guard, the U.S. National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service and the governor's office.
   Miller's subcommittee held 12 hearings in the last congressional
session on legislation to allow oil development in the Arctic
National Wildlife Refuge, near Prudhoe Bay. The bill was never
voted out of the subcommitee.
   The legislation was reintroduced this session, but no hearings
have been held in the House yet. The bill has already passed the
Senate Committee on Energy and Natural Resources and is awaiting a
vote by the full Senate.
</TEXT>
