<FIRST>r i AM-Venezuela     04-03 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apartment Owners Block Traffic to Protest Boost in Interest Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of apartment owners blocked
streets in a lower-class neighborhood of the capital Monday to
protest austerity policies that led to soaring mortgage interest
rates.
   The protesters in the Baruta district shouted against the plan
aimed at fighting inflation that ran 35 percent last year in an
oil-producing country hit hard by lower prices on crude.
   Office workers who live in the district said morning bus traffic
was halted and many people were forced to walk to get to work.
   Protests prompted by the the economic measures left at least 270
people dead last month, according to government figures, although
unofficial estimates place the toll between 300 and 500.
   The new interest rate policy allows banks to float rates on
loans and on deposits according to market pressures. Government
economists have indicated the free-floating interest rates are
necessary to prevent capital flight and promote savings.
   But critics of the policy charge that the new interest rates,
which have gone from 13 percent on an average mortgage contract to
28 percent as of last month with promises of higher rates to come,
will force thousands out of their homes.
   Neighborhood associations and political figures have filed a
lawsuit in the Venezuelan supreme court contesting the interest
rate policy. Neighborhood groups have threatened to withhold their
payments until the court decides the case.
   News reports have indicated President Carlos Andres Perez may be
forced to adjust the program by creating additional subsidies for
homeowners or placing a ceiling on interest rates.
   The interest rate changes are part of an austerity plan begun to
comply with International Monetary Fund plans for a realignment of
Venezuela's economy.
</TEXT>
