<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1807EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HighwayKillings     04-03 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Killings,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eighth Massachusetts Victim Identified, Tipster Comes Forward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The eighth victim of an apparent
serial killer was identified Monday as a 27-year-old New Bedford
woman, and authorities said a previously anonymous letter writer is
aiding investigators.
   The body found Friday along Route 88 in Westport was identified
as that of Mary Rose Santos, a mother of two young boys who had
been missing since July 16.
   Meanwhile, investigators, aided by dogs trained to sniff out the
dead, resumed their search Monday for more bodies along highways in
southern Massachusetts. The dogs are trained with an aromatic
compound called ``Cadavarine.''
   Like the previous seven victims, Santos had ties to this port
city's drug community, said Bristol County District Attorney Ronald
A. Pina.
   An anonymous letter reached Pina on March 16, telling him that
investigators might find a body along Route 88. If a body was
found, the author said he might come forward.
   After two boys found Santos' body, the informant contacted
authorities.
   ``He witnessed an event taking place along Route 88,'' said Jim
Martin, a spokesman for Pina. ``This person is providing us with
some good information and we need to protect this person.''
   Martin added that he did not wish to say whether the informant
was male or female.
   Investigators have met with the informant in secret and at
various locations to maintain the informant's anonymity, Martin
said.
   A special grand jury was to reconvene Tuesday to hear testimony
from 18 subpoenaed witnesses, but Martin said that the informant
would not be among them because the news media will be present
outside the court.
   The informant's testimony could be taken by a police officer and
then presented to the grand jury, he said.
   Connecticut State Police loaned two ``body dogs'' and
Massachusetts State Police added one to the search Monday, Martin
said.
   Three of the eight victims found along routes 140, 88 and
Interstate 195 in towns near New Bedford were discovered by police
dogs.
   Massachusetts has 15 patrol dogs that have undergone a 10- to
16-week course to learn to search for bodies, according to State
Trooper Kathy Barrett, whose German Shephard, Cyros, has been busy
in the highway killings case.
   Cyros is also trained to do routine patrol work and search for
missing persons or fugitives. The Connecticut dogs, under the
direction of Trooper Andy Rebman, work only on body searches.
   Rebman trains many of the region's police ``body dogs'' as part
of a New England consortium of state police.
   At first, handlers try to make a game out of the training by
``inserting'' the smell of a decaying corpse on a favorite toy or
ball. The trainers then hide the ball in thick brush and the dog
seeks it.
   The smell is placed on the ball with ``Cadavarine,'' a compound
that simulates the odor of a dead body. It is also known as
1,5-Diaminopentane and sold by Pfaltz and Bauer Inc. of Waterbury,
Conn.
   ``Cadaverine is a chemical equivalent of the gases and odors
that are given off by a decaying body,'' said New Hampshire State
Police Cpt. Ernest Loomis.
   New Hampshire had its first dog trained for body work just six
months ago. Loomis said handlers are careful to wear rubber gloves
when training Kaizer with the Cadaverine because of the potent and
long-lasting nature of the odor.
   ``A little of it goes a long way,'' he said.
   Massachusetts State Trooper Walter Keenan, whose shephard,
Stark, does body work, said Cadavarine sells for about $50 an ounce.
</TEXT>
