<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1807EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia-Glance     04-03 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia-Glance,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glance At 23-Year War In Namibia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief overview of the 23-year
war in Namibia between the South African-led security forces and
the guerrillas of the South-West Africa People's Organization.
   ORIGIN: SWAPO began military operations in 1966 after South
Africa defied a United Nations resolution to relinquish control of
the territory it had captured from the Germans in World War I. An
estimated 20,000 people, mostly SWAPO guerrillas, have been killed.
   FIGHTING: Almost all the fighting has taken place in northern
Namibia and involved bush battles and sabotage attacks carried out
by SWAPO forces that infiltrated from bases in southern Angola.
SWAPO has never been able to establish permanent bases inside
Namibia, and only a small number of guerrillas have been active in
the territory at any time. Until the fighting in recent days, both
sides had observed an informal cease-fire since August.
   SIZE: South African military officials estimate SWAPO has 8,000
members in its military wing. SWAPO says it also has 80,000
supporters at refugee camps outside Namibia, although the U.N. has
put the figure at about 60,000.
   South Africa had an estimated 50,000 troops in Namibia,
concentrated in the north. The figure includes Namibians belonging
to the South-West Africa Territorial Force. The number must be
reduced to 12,000 by mid-May and 1,500 by July 1 under the peace
accords signed last December.
   Also, South Africa has agreed to cut the territorial police
force from 8,300 to 6,000 during the independence process.
   The United Nations has authorized 4,650 peacekeeping troops for
the operation, but only about 1,000 have arrived.
   ANGOLA: In the civil war in neighboring Angola, 50,000 Cuban
troops have supported the Marxist government in its fight against
the UNITA rebel movement, which is backed by the United States, and
until the recent peace accord, South Africa.
   UNITA bases in southern Angola are to the east of the SWAPO
camps. The two guerrilla groups are hostile toward one another, but
have virtually no contact. The Cubans and the Angolans support
SWAPO, but do not directly assist the guerrillas with attacks
inside Namibia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
