<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     04-03 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shouts of `Long Live the King' As Hapsburgs Leave Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands cheered and people shouted
``Long Live the King!'' when Otto von Hapsburg and other members of
the family left a church Monday after a Mass for his mother Zita,
the last queen of Hungary.
   Inside St. Matthew's Church, where Hungary's rulers were
crowned, parishioners sang the national anthem as Mass was
celebrated by Cardinal Laszlo Paskai, the Roman Catholic primate.
Zita died March 14 at age 96.
   One report said the anthem was sung again as Otto, eldest son of
the the queen, and several other Hapsburgs left the church, but
witness Janos Gudenus said he was not aware of it being sung
outside. He is a descendant of the Gudenus barons of Hungary.
   The requiem in Budapest, now a communist capital, occurred two
days after the most elaborate funeral Vienna has seen in more than
70 years. Zita, also the last empress of Austria, was buried at the
Capuchin Vault, the last resting place of the Hapsburg dynasty.
   Otto von Hapsburg made his first official visit to Hungary last
month. He was cheered at Karl Marx University, where he delivered a
lecture, and at other public appearances.
   At the town of Nagyarmos on the Danube River, between 5,000 and
6,000 people demonstrated against a hydropower project Monday and
demanded the Hungarian government resign, state radio reported.
   About 130,000 Hungarians have signed a petition asking that
construction stop and a referendum be held.
   The Nagymaros dam and power plant is being built in conjunction
with a similar complex upstream at Gabcikovo, Czechoslovakia.
Parliament voted earlier this month to continue the project, which
is financed largely with Austrian money in provided in exchange for
future power supplies.
   Critics say the dams will destroy wetlands and wildlife and
endanger supplies of drinking water for hundreds of thousands of
Hungarians.
   The demonstrators, who gathered near the site, demanded the
entire government resign but particularly the environment minister,
Laszlo Maroti.
