<FIRST>u a AM-DefenseInvestigation 1stLd-Writethru a0619 04-03 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0619,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Accused of `Bribing, Cheating' as First Pentagon Trial Begins</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Mortenson in 13th graf, Schnittjer's attorney,
and adds 14th graf with 1st witness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three former defense contracting
executives heard themselves accused of ``bribing ... cheating ...
lying'' on Monday at the start of the first trial stemming from the
federal investigation into fraud in the Pentagon's purchasing
system.
   The defendants' lawyers said they had done nothing wrong.
   The three former Teledyne Electronics executives _ George Kaub,
Dale Schnittjer and Eugene Sullivan _ are charged with bribery,
conspiracy and making false statements in an indictment handed up
by the grand jury three months ago.
   All worked for the Newbury Park, Calif., company that is a
subsidiary of Teledyne ndustries, which has already pleaded guilty
in the case. In addition, a former Navy procurement official and
two private consultants have pleaded guilty and agreed to cooperate
with prosecutors.
   ``This is a case about bribing, about cheating, about lying,''
said Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert DeHenzel Jr. in his opening
arguments in the case before U.S. District Judge Richard Williams.
   DeHenzel outlined a complicated scheme in which he said the
executives agreed to pay money to private consultant William
Parkin, who in turn indirectly bribed a Navy official, Stuart
Berlin, for inside information about a $24 million contract to
build hand-held radar test equipment. The middleman between Parkin
and Berlin was consultant Fred Lackner, DeHenzel said.
   ``Berlin provided Lackner with confidential information. ...A
lot of the information should not have been given to anyone outside
government,'' he said.
   Kaub and Sullivan were initially involved in agreeing to a
$10,000 contract that Parkin had with Teledyne starting in late
1985, the prosecutor said. The initial contract called for Parkin
to provide help in reversing a decision that might have dimmed
Teledyne's chances for the contract by setting it aside for a small
business entity.
   Once Teledyne was awarded the deal in June, 1987, the agreement
called for Parkin to receive $150,000 over two years for his
services, the prosecutor said.
   Kaub was Teledyne Electronics' executive vice president dealing
with government contracts. Sullivan and his successor, Schnittjer,
were also executive vice presidents.
   Lawyers for the three men denied that their clients had done
anything wrong and argued that they were victims of a conspiracy
between Parkin and his associates.
   ``No one can be found guilty unless they know what is going
on,'' said George O'Connell, Sullivan's attorney.
   Mark Tuohey, Kaub's attorney, told the jury that when they
evaluate the evidence they will find ``there was a conspiracy of
silence'' between Parkin and those whom he had agreed to pay for
his information.
   Schnittjer's attorney, Stan Mortenson, said his client didn't
even begin work at the Newbury Park facility until a month after
the government contract was negotiated. ``Schnittjer is an innocent
victim ... wrongly charged with 14 crimes,'' Mortenson said.
   The government's first witness in the case, Charles Jones, an
Air Force contracting officer, testified that if information was
released to one contractor the same data should have been made
available to everyone.
   The government began its investigation into the
$150-billion-a-year Pentagon procurement system nearly three years
ago but the probe was not publicly revealed until June 1988. Agents
used telephone wiretaps and tape-recorded conversations to gather
evidence in the case that centers on allegations that consultants
paid bribes to get information useful to their clients in winning
contracts.
   The tapes are expected to be played in court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890403-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1840EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Baseball     04-03 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Baseball,1st ld-writethru, a0624,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 15th graf to update with final score</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Mubarak, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, who once captained the Yale
baseball team, pitched his first ball as president Monday at the
season opener between the Baltimore Orioles and the Boston Red Sox.
   As the president of Egypt and a sellout crowd of 54,000 looked
on, southpaw Bush hurled a game-opening pitch that was a little
high and outside. Orioles catcher Mickey Tettleton had no problem
snagging it over his right shoulder.
   ``He caught it before it started breaking,'' Bush insisted
afterwards.
   Bush brought with him Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, who told
reporters this was the first baseball game he had been to although
``I saw it on television several times.''
   Bush defended his pitch later during a picture-taking session in
a glass-enclosed box above third base.
   ``What do you think? You're an objective judge?'' he asked
baseball great Ted Williams, a longtime friend.
   ``A high, hard fastball,'' Williams answered.
   Bush then asked A. Bartlett Giamatti, the commissioner of
baseball, for his opinion. ``Superb. I didn't see it, but I
heard,'' the commissioner said.
   Bush and Mubarak munched on hamburgers and hot dogs and drank
soft drinks in Orioles cups.
   At one point, Mubarak put on an Orioles baseball cap for
photographers. Bush's tie was in the Orioles' team colors _ orange
and black.
   Mubarak said that he was enjoying the game and that Bush was ``a
good teacher, of course. He was the captain of the biggest team in
the United States.''
   ``That's what I told him,'' joked Bush.
   Also in the box were Secretary of State James A. Baker III,
Chief of Staff John Sununu and Budget Director Richard Darman,
wearing a Red Sox cap.
   The sky was overcast when Bush and Mubarak left Washington by
helicopter. By the time the game began shortly after 2 p.m.,
however, the sun had poked through the clouds and was shining
brightly.
   Bush and his party stayed through the fifth inning, missing most
of the game's action. When he left, the score was Orioles 1, Red
Sox 0. The Orioles went on to win, 5-4, in 12 innings.
   Bush was captain of the 1948 Yale baseball team. A first baseman
known for his fielding, Bush's batting average was a modest .167.
   But that didn't stop him of dreaming of ``a fat contract to play
professional baseball,'' as he put it in his 1987 biography
``Looking Forward.''
   Bush, who bats right-handed but throws with his left, has been
an avid baseball fan ever since. He freout first
balls in his eight years as vice president and during the 1988
presidential campaign.
   After ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' by rock singer Joan Jett,
Bush strode jauntily to the mound in his shirt sleeves. Catcher
Tettleton moved forward a teps to catch the president's pitch.
   Of the 26 opening day pitchers in major league baseball, 23 are
paid more than Bush's $200,000 salary as president.
   Of those, Orioles starting pitcher Dave Schmidt will make
$625,000 this season and Red Sox opening pitcher Roger Clemens,
$2.3 million.
   In addition tfelong enthusiasm for the game, Bush has
baseball in his family. His oldest son, George W. Bush, recently
became the leader of a partnership ts Rangers.
</TEXT>
