<FIRST>u i AM-PLO     04-03 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Spokesman Welcomes Bush Call For Peace Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Mubarak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat's chief
adviser on Monday welcomed a call by President Bush for a Middle
East peace conference and Israel's withdrawal from its occupied
territories as an ``important and serious development.''
   Bassam Abu Sharif told The Associated Press the Palestine
Liberation Organization feels ``this will give a real push for
peace efforts in the Middle East.''
   ``We hope that the positive position of President Bush would
convince the Israeli government that peace could be established in
the Middle East on the basis of a two-state solution, two states
living side-by-side in peace,'' Abu Sharif said.
   Bush also told a White House news conference after a meeting
with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak that he supported
``achievement of Palestinian political rights.''
   Earlier the PLO central committee, ending a four-day meeting in
Tunis, ruled out any let-up in the Palestinian uprising in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip in exchange for Israeli-sponsored elections.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir announced last week his
government would allow limited elections in the occupied
territories, and withdraw troops from major Arab cities, if the
Palestinian uprising stopped.
   But the Israeli leader, due in Washington for talks this week,
envisions only limited autonomy for the Palestinians and refuses to
talk with the PLO, which he views as a terrorist group.
   ``The Central Committee announced to the world that the
intefadeh (uprising) will not cease and our people's struggle will
continue,'' said the statement telefaxed to the AP in Cyprus by the
official Palestinian press agency, WAFA.
   At least 419 Palestinians and 16 Israelis have been killed in
the nearly 16-month-old uprising against Israel's military
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza strip.
   The 70-member Central Committee is an interim group of the
450-seat Palestine National Council, which is scheduled to meet
once a year. The Central Committee and the smaller, 15-member
Executive Committee, make policy recommendations to be weighed by
the full body.
   The Central Committee reviewed the United States-PLO talks,
``welcomed the continuation of these talks and stressed their
importance,'' the statement said. The United States began talks
with the PLO in December for the first time in 13 years after
Arafat renounced terrorism and said he recognized Israel's right to
exist.
   Also Monday, the Persian Gulf newspaper Al-Khaleej reported that
Tunisia had barred the entry of Abul Abbas, the leader of the
Palestine Liberation Front who has accused of masterminding the
hijacking of the Italian cruise vessel Achille Lauro in 1985.
   Al-Khaleej, a United Arab Emirates newspaper based in Sharjah,
quoted a Palestine Liberation Front source as saying Abul Abbas was
not able to attend the Central Committee meeting.
   Abul Abbas was asked to stop trying to enter Tunisia, but the
Tunisian government gave no reason for banning him, said the
unnamed source in a dispatch from Algeria.
   There was no immediate confirmation of the report from Tunisia,
where the PLO, umbrella for all guerrilla factions including Abbas'
group, is headquartered.
   Abul Abbas, whose full name is Mohammed Abbas, has been branded
as a terrorist in the United States since the 1985 incident in
which an American citizen, 69-year-old Leon Klinghoffer, was killed.
   The United States reportedly wants Abul Abbas expelled from the
PLO, and the paper, which is known for its hard-line stance on the
Palestinian issue, dropped hints that Arafat was complying.
   Abul Abbas was convicted in absentia in an Italian court and
sentenced to life for the Achille Lauro affair.
</TEXT>
