<FIRST>u a AM-BridgeCollapse     04-03 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bridge Collapse,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Points To High Water</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COVINGTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jackhammer crews Monday began breaking
up 200 tons of concrete that crashed down on at least three cars
and a tractor-trailer truck when a section of a U.S. highway bridge
collapsed into a river.
   Seven people died and an eighth was reported missing in the
accident Saturday night about 50 miles north of Memphis.
   Authorities planned to bring in a 60-ton National Guard crane to
remove the concrete once engineers pronounced the bridge safe to
support the equipment, said Jim Thacker, regional manager of the
Tennessee Emergency Management Agency.
   A possible eighth victim was a local man missing since Saturday
night when the bridge fell.
   ``He's missing and he should have been on this road at that
time,' said Jacky Carter, an investigator with the emergency agency.
   Divers found the other victims in the swirling, coffee-colored
water Saturday and Sunday. There were no survivors in the vehicles
known to have plunged into the 30-foot-deep water, authorities said.
   Bill Tucker, county executive for Lauderdale County, said
authorities know of no other local residents who might be in the
river.
   ``There's a possibility that somebody from out of state or
something could be somewhere further on down, but that's just a
remote possibility,'' Tucker said. ``We think we've got it isolated
to one area.''
   But Terry Petty, a diver with the Tennessee Highway Patrol, said
the water was so dark it was hard to tell if other vehicles might
be in the river. The current was eight to 10 knots, he said.
   ``With this current, if a car went off after it fell (and was
not trapped under the concrete), it could be a mile down the
river,'' Petty said.
   The 55-year-old bridge, eight-tenths of a mile long, carried two
north-bound lanes of U.S. Highway 51 across the Hatchie River about
five miles north of Covington at the Tipton-Lauderdale county line.
   A companion bridge, built in the mid-1970s to carry the
highway's south-bMilliganes, was unaffected but has been closed
indefinitely whiMilligan's hit-and-run single.
   After Mike Smithson replaced Bob Stanley, Worthington flared a
1-0 pitch into left-center field past Ellis Burks' dive, foiling a
Boston formation of five infielders.
   Brian Holton, acquired in an off-season trade that sent Eddie
Murray to Los Angeles, pitched 4 1-3 scoreless innings for the
victory. Stanley entered after Lee Smith left with a pulled groin
and took the loss, Boston's fourth straight defeat on opening say.
   The Orioles set a major league record last year for futility at
the start of the season. This time, Bush helped Baltimore beat
another Massachusetts rival. The president attended the game with
Egyptian leader Hosni Mubarak.
   Clemens, 6-2 lifetime against the Orioles, left after Brady
Anderson led off the eighth inning with his second double. He
pitched seven innings, allowing seven hits and four runs, as he
earned his second no-decision in two opening-day starts.
   Cal Ripken's three-run homer in the sixth put Baltimore ahead
4-3. Anderson doubled, Phil Bradley walked and Ripken sent a 2-1
pitch over the left-field wall.
   Boston tied the score with a run in the seventh when Jody Reed
singled home Nick Esasky, who led off with a double and took third
on a ground out by Rich Gedman.
   Trailing 1-0, Boston scored three times in the sixth inning.
Dwight Evans' RBI double tied the score and Mike Greenwell hit a
two-run homer off starter Dave Schmidt.
   The Orioles took a 1-0 lead in the fourth when Anderson walked,
stole second and scored on a single by Joe Orsulak.
   Baltimore rookie Steve Finley had to leave the game after the
third inning after crashing into the wall in right-center field
after making a catch on Esasky's drive. X-rays on Finley showed a
sprained right shoulder.
   Wade Boggs, a five-time American League batting champion, went
2-for-4. The Red Sox have tried to trade him because of the
commotion his affair with Margo Adams caused, but have found no
takers.
