<FIRST>r w AM-Thornburgh-Computer     04-03 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh-Computer,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clear Thornburgh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department's ethics office found
no basis to investigate an allegation that Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh planned to use a government computer for political
purposes, officials said Monday.
   The Office of Professional Responsibility conducted a
preliminary inquiry after an unidentified person alleged that last
fall, Thornburgh aides sought to compile a list of the attorney
general's contacts dating back to his days as Pennsylvania
governor, said David Runkel, a special assistant to the attorney
general.
   The OPR preliminary inquiry concluded there was no basis for
further investigation of the allegation that the names of 10,000 of
Thornburgh's political supporters from Pennsylvania would be placed
on the computerized mailing list, Runkel said.
   ``That had never been contemplated, suggested or planned,''
Runkel said.
   But the project has become a matter of dispute in the
department, where some employees jokingly dubbed it ``DICKPAC,''
reflecting concerns the computerized list would be misused for
political purposes, said a department source, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Runkel said the plan, still under active consideration, was
merely ``to put the A.G.'s meeting and schedules on computers.''
   It is envisioned as a way to keep pertinent information about
the attorney general's contacts so that when Thornburgh ``meets
with a person he can say `We met last July and I know you were
interested in X, Y, Z,'' he said.
   ``There are a lot of people who communicate with the attorney
general,'' Runkel said. Some are from Pennsylvania and ``some
obviously are political supporters.''
   The OPR inquiry found ``there was nothing wrong'' with using
Justice Department computers to keep track of the people Thornburgh
meets, Runkel said.
   The brief report concluded ```Why are we wasting our time on
this stuff?''' said Runkel. It concluded ``this is a
misunderstanding by one person of what someone else said.''
   ``The whole complaint was based on a misunderstanding,'' Runkel
said. He declined to release the page-and-a-half document saying:
``It's an investigative report, we don't make it public.''
   The inquiry was conducted after Thornburgh aide Murray Dickman
asked the Office of Litigation Support in the civil division to
write a computer program for the project, said the department
source.
   The project created consternation in litigation support office,
where those involved feared it might be misused for political
purposes and violate the Justice Department's ethics guidelines
that prohibit use of government facilities for unofficial business,
said the source.
   John R. Bolton, the assistant attorney general in charge of the
civil division, confronted Dickman and Robert Ross Jr.,
Thornburgh's executive assistant, about the project after learning
of its existence, said the source.
   Runkel also took issue with this account, saying ``there was
never anything to suspend.''
   ``Civil got involved in this only because the computers up here
are hooked into the system it has ownership or has control over,''
Runkel said.
   Aides decided that division's litigation system known as AMICUS
was not a good idea, Runkel said.
   Runkel said aides concluded they could ``use it on some PC and
buy a $50 program and start plugging it in.''
   Bolton declined to comment. Dickman did not return a reporter's
telephone call.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
