<FIRST>r i AM-Austria-Hungary     04-03 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Austria-Hungary,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Shoppers Invade Austria for Final Fling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarians crossed the border in huge
numbers Monday to buy video equipment and other goods on a last
spree before their communist government raises the cost of bringing
the booty home.
   Austrian television said 300,000 shoppers visited Austria and
that 130,000 of them reached Vienna.
   Most Hungarian businesses were closed Monday, the eve of a
national holiday observed on the date Soviet soldiers liberated
Budapest from the Nazis in 1945.
   Cars were backed up more than 40 miles on the Hungarian side of
the frontier by midmorning, the Austrian Automobile and Touring
Club reported.
   On Saturday, Hungary's customs duties will rise from from 30
percent to 45, a special low rate of 15 percent for computers and
video machines will end and duty-free allowances will be reduced
sharply.
   Under current rules, each member of a family of four may bring
back duty-free goods worth $200 on each trip and the shares may be
combined to cover a major purchase. On Saturday, the per-person
allowance will be cut in half and no totaling will be allowed.
   Official figures in Budapest say Hungarians spent the equivalent
of about $600,000 in Austria between January 1988, when visa-free
travel to the West began, and Feburary of this year.
   How Hungarians acquire the necessary Austrian currency is not
clear, but some sources are the black market and relatives, friends
or other connections in the West.
   A similar rush of Hungarian customers, who can travel to the
West without visas as often as they want, was registered Nov. 7,
1988, when more than 100,000 Hungarians went shopping across the
border.
   On Monday, traffic was snarled in many parts of Burgenland,
Austria's easternmost province, and thousands of Hungarian cars
contributed to the usual congestion in Vienna.
   A policeman in Burgenland, who asked that his name not be used,
described it as a ``madhouse.'' A radio reporter described the
congestion there as ``hardly imaginable.''
   In Vienna's Mariahilferstrasse, a favorite shopping street,
Hungarians lined up at 6 a.m. outside closed stores that sell video
machines, other electronic equipment and household appliances.
   An Associated Press reporter saw at least 23 Hungarian buses
parked near Mariahilferstrassse. Scores of Hungarians were seen
carrying everything from color television sets to computers,
refrigerators and stereo equipment.
   A storekeeper said business was three times normal. A large shoe
store advertised products in both German and Hungarian.
   Reports said Hungarians arrived in Zurndorf at 2 a.m., parked
their cars everywhere and roused the village, so the outraged
residents went on strike and kept their children home from school.
</TEXT>
