<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-GoldRuble     04-03 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Gold Ruble,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Economists Debating Convertible Ruble Backed by Gold, Goods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Soviet economist said Monday that
officials are debating establishment of a second currency that
would be convertible and backed by gold, foreign currency reserves
and export goods.
   Abel Aganbegyan, secretary of the economics department of the
Academy of Sciences, said the special-purpose ruble would be issued
in amounts large enough to facilitate foreign trade, which is now
hampered by the Soviet Union's shortage of hard currency.
   It could be tied in with proposals to create special foreign
trade zones on the Finnish border and in the Soviet Far East, where
foreign firms would enjoy tariff, tax and other benefits, he said.
   He noted that the ``gold ruble,'' as some have called the
proposed currency, is still just an idea, and is opposed by some
Soviet economists. He alluded to the fact that it would have to be
accepted by the major Western banks to work.
   Pepsico Chairman Donald Kendall, speaking at the same news
conference, said that some companies would buy a hard ruble and
some would not, ``but I'd certainly rather have a gold-backed ruble
than the one we have now.''
   Pepsico is one of the Soviet Union's major trading partners,
exchanging Pepsi for Stolichnaya vodka.
   The second currency would be an interim step while the Soviet
Union is trying to bring the regular ruble closer to
convertibility, Aganbegyan said.
   Officials say that may take a decade or more, as the Soviet
Union now has little to sell on world markets and the official
exchange rate of $1.60 to the ruble is far too high. In comparison,
the black market rate is 10-25 cents per ruble.
</TEXT>
