<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-Nuclear     04-03 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Nuclear,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Media Denounces Reports On Iraqi Nuclear Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government media on Monday denounced
reports in the American press saying Iraq plans to produce nuclear
warheads.
   Front page editorials in three state-run newspapers accused
Israel of orchestrating a campaign that they said was aimed at
``defaming Iraq and influencing the peace talks with Iran.'' Iran
and Iraq agreed to a cease-fire in August that ended their
eight-year-old war.
   The papers did not specifically deny the reports about nuclear
weapons.
   Last week, the Washington Post said Iraq has embarked on a crash
program to produce a nuclear warhead within two years.
   An Israeli general said Sunday there was some basis to reports
that Iraq is engaged in an effort to build nuclear warheads for
missiles that could reach Israel.
   Maj. Gen. Ehud Barak, deputy armed forces chief of staff, in an
interview on Israeli Television, was asked about the Washington
Post report and he said, ``Iraq has not abandoned its aim to reach
nuclear capability. As far as I know, these reports have at least a
nucleus of truth.''
   Iraq's government-owned Al-Joumhouriya newspaper said the
reports were leaked by Israeli officials to the U.S. media to
distract world public opinion from the Palestinian uprising in the
Israeli-occupied territories and to pave the way for new attacks
against Iraqi nuclear installations.
   ``If the aim is to frighten Iraq and launch a pre-emptive strike
... you should understand that Iraq is fully alert and will be
ready to answer back with all the potential at its disposal,'' the
newspaper said.
   Israeli warplanes destroyed Iraq's Osirak nuclear reactor in
1981.
   The ruling Baath Party's Al-Thawra newspaper said the American
press ignored Israel's nuclear weapons program while spreading lies
about the alleged danger of Iraq's nuclear program.
   Al-Qadissiya, the army newspaper, said any Israeli action would
be dealt with in ``an appropriate way.''
   ``They will get nothing but humiliation, disgrace and
destruction,'' it said.
</TEXT>
