<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Detainees     04-03 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Detainees,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Africa Frees Three Black Hunger Strikers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three black prisoners who staged
hunger strikes to protest their detention without trial were
released from custody Monday, a lawyer said.
   The three were freed from St. Aidan's Hospital, where they had
been treated for the effects of their fast, said attorney Dhaya
Pillay.
   Miss Pillay said one of the men, Sandile Thusi, had refused to
eat for 38 days _ the longest fast of more than 500 detainees held
without trial who have staged hunger strikes since January.
   The attorney said Thusi was placed under restrictions that
require him to report to police twice a day and bar him from
talking to the news media or leaving his house from dusk to dawn.
   She identified the two other men freed as Isaac Nzuza and Paulos
Mvulana but did not say if they were placed under restrictive
orders.
   South Africa's white-dominated government says it has released
almost 600 detainees since the hunger strikes began. Human rights
groups say about 250 people who have not been charged remain
imprisoned and many of the others freed were placed under severe
restrictions.
   An estimated 30,000 people, almost all blacks, have been
detained for varying lengths of time during the 33-month-old state
of emergency.
</TEXT>
