<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 2028EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     04-03 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drnovsek Will Become Yugoslavia's New President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Janez Drnovsek, a 38-year-old
Slovenian economist, will become communist Yugoslavia's first
directly elected president next month.
   Drnovsek, a member of the federal parliament virtually unknown
outside Slovenia, defeated Marko Bulc, 62, who is president of the
republic's trade chamber, in elections Sunday for Slovenia's
representative to the largely ceremonial collective presidency.
   Under Yugoslavia's rotating system, the six republics and two
provinces each have a representative in the presidency and take
turns leading the nation's top body.
   This time it is Slovenia's turn, and Drnovsek takes over in
mid-May from Raif Dizdarevic of Bosnia. The ninth seat in the
presidency is reserved for the Communist Party chief.
   The economist won 56 percent of votes and Bulc 41 percent,
according to unofficial results quoted by the official Tanjug news
agency.
   By government count, 87.5 percent of Slovenia's 1.47 million
registered voters took part.
   President Josip Broz Tito created the rotating presidency to
avoid power struggles after his death and prevent the emergence of
a dominant leader who could disturb the country's ethnic balance.
   Slovenia has led the drive for more democracy in this
single-party state and has allowed several non-communist, human
rights and political groups to function freely.
   It also has allowed a Social Democratic Union, which claims to
be Yugoslavia's first independent political party since the
communists took power after World War II.
   Drnovsek, who will become Yugoslavia's youngest president, is a
doctor of economic sciences who worked in several Yugoslav
companies and banks as well as in the diplomatic service.
   He reportedly has specialized in his country's economic matters
and monetary and credit policies.
   Drnovsek is a strong supporter of the drive to have non-aligned
Yugoslavia join the European Economic Community.
   Bulc and Drnovsek remained in the Slovenian race from six
original candidates after a complicated election system began at
grassroot levels.
   Previously, members of the presidency were elected by republican
legislatures that gave rubber-stamp approval to single candidates
picked by the Communist Party.
   The southern republic of Montenegro will choose its
representative among three candidates in an April 9 ballot. The
other republics namd their members through the old system.
   Slovenian candidates were involved in a Western-style campaign
of speeches and television debates in which they faced probing
questions and had to defend their programs.
   Both candidates called for radical market-oriented reforms to
overcome the country's deep economic crisis, which includes 400
percent annual inflation and a $21 billion foreign debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
