<DOCNO> AP890403-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 2039EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Namibia     04-03 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Investigators Report Major Border Crossing by SWAPO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. investigators have found that
guerrillas of the South-West Africa People's Organization mounted a
major invasion from Angola into Namibia over the weekend, according
to diplomats.
   The findings of the U.N. investigators were relayed to
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, who briefed Security
Council members, said three senior diplomats from Western nations,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Their findings were incorporated into a report the U.N. chief
presented to the Security Council on Monday evening under unusually
heavy security.
   More than 1,000 SWAPO guerrillas infiltrated northern Namibia,
but their motive was not known, said the diplomats.
   Since fighting broke out Saturday, 129 SWAPO guerrillas and 18
Namibian territorial police have been killed, according to
Namibia's police force.
   South Africa says the SWAPO rebels infiltrated Namibia from
southern Angola; SWAPO officials say their men were already in the
country and only fired in self-defense.
   Publicly, U.N. officials scrupulously avoided making any comment
that might be interpreted as blaming one side or the other.
   But SWAPO's foreign secretary, Theo-Ben Gurirab, castigated the
world body for allowing South African military units to reinforce
territorial police in their battle against the guerrillas.
   ``Our people are being butchered under the United Nations
flag,'' said Gurirab.
   He spoke as the 15 members of the Security Council met privately
to hear the report on the clashes.
   Part of the mission of the U.N. Transition Assistance Group was
to see that guerrillas of the South West Africa People's
Organization were confined to bases in Angola and Zambia, and make
sure no one infiltrated Namibia.
   However, only about 1,000 members of UNTAG, which was envisioned
to have a full strength of 4,650 peacekeepers, were in Namibia by
Friday night, when gun battles broke out between SWAPO rebels and
territorial police.
   ``UNTAG is not yet fully in Namibia,'' Perez de Cuellar said.
``We have 300 men in the northern part of the area. You cannot say
it is a failure.''
   Perez de Cuellar's report in January to the Security Council on
UNTAG's mission recommended 4,650 peacekeepers, but also asked for
authority to send as many as 7,500 if the situation required more
soldiers.
   The bulk of the troops are expected to arrive during April,
bringing the force to nearly full strength by the end of the month.
   Undersecretary-General Marrack Goulding, the U.N.'s chief
peacekeeping official, was dispatched to Luanda, Angola, to meet
with Angolan officials and with three U.N. peacekeepers who
investigated the weekend clashes.
   Goulding was expected to arrive in Luanda on Tuesday.
   A Western diplomat involved in the negotiations that led up to
the independence plan for Namibia said SWAPO argued throughout that
it had fighters in the country who should be allowed to maintain
U.N.-supervised barracks in Namibia on the same basis as South
Africa.
   ``Possibly they were trying to get men in at the 11th hour to
bolster their argument that they had them in Namibia, and therefore
they should have bases in the country,'' said the diplomat,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Until Saturday, the United Nations recognized SWAPO as the
legitimate representative of the Namibian people.
   With the inauguration of the U.N.-supervised independence plan,
the United Nations recognized SWAPO as one political force among
many contending for power in Namibia, and was to remain impartial.
</TEXT>
