<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 2209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MeteoriteSighting     04-03 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meteorite Sighting,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coloradans Report Daytime Meteorite Sightings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``brilliant blue'' object with a streaking
yellow tail that was seen rocketing across Colorado skies Monday
may have been a rare daytime meteorite, a planetarium spokeswoman
said.
   ``From all the details we have been able to get, it sounds like
it was a meteorite,'' said Suzy Gurton, program supervisor at Fiske
Planetarium in Boulder.
   ``We haven't been able to determine yet whether it landed or
exploded before it hit the earth,'' she said.
   Reported sightings of the object filtered into atmospheric and
space-related agencies shortly after noon from metropolitan Denver,
Salida in south-central Colorado, and Garden City and Salinas in
Kansas.
   ``We got lots of calls on it. It doesn't correlate with anything
we're tracking,'' said Capt. Thomas Neiman, a spokesman for the
North American Defense Command near Colorado Springs.
   NORAD, which tracks about 7,000 objects in space, received calls
about the object from Federal Aviation Administration officials at
Longmont and from Scott Air Force Base in Illinois, Neiman said.
   A spokesman for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration in Boulder said he received a query about the object
from Salinas, Kan.
   Gurton said one of the people who contacted the planetarium said
the object had ``brilliant blue color for the head. ... There was a
yellow tail streaking behind it.''
   She said the witnesses indicated it was traveling north, but
``where it landed, we don't know.''
   In Salida, witnesses said there was a loud boom and the object
appeared to burst into flame.
   Gurton said it is fairly unusual to see a meteor in the daytime.
   ``It doesn't happen often anywhere,'' she said.
   Planetarium officials were attempting to pinpoint where the
meteorite may have landed by tracking the reports they received,
she said.
</TEXT>
