<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-US 1stLd-Writethru a0658 04-03 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0788</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Hints Will Express Opposition to Bush Position</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Shamir comments at airport.
Pick up 11th pvs, ``Shamir has...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush-Mubarak, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir indicated Tuesday
that during his U.S. visit he will state his opposition to
President Bush's call for an end to Israeli occupation of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip and his endorsement of an international peace
conference.
   ``My position on all these issues is known. I'll have something
to discuss with the leaders of the United States,'' Shamir said as
he left for a 10-day visit to the United States.
   ``We shall insist that negotiations be held within a reasonable
framework, and be conducted directly and without preconditions,''
he said.
   ``We are looking for the right solutions ... for the problems we
are facing. I hope that the leaders of the United States will find
an interest in our proposals, (and) there are some proposals,'' he
said at Ben Gurion Airport near Tel Aviv.
   Bush, speaking Monday after meeting in Washington with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak, called for a ``properly structured''
Middle East peace conference _ a concept which Shamir opposes.
   ``Egypt and the United States share the goals of security for
Israel, end of the occupation and achievement of Palestinian
political rights,'' Bush said.
   Shortly before Shamir's departure, about 500 hundred activists
from the anti-war group Peace Now marched through downtown
Jerusalem to Shamir's residence with burning torches.
   They shouted slogans such as ``Talk with the PLO'' and ``Two
states for two peoples.''
   ``It's very important that (Shamir) takes into account that a
large segment of the Israeli public sees this special time as an
historic opportunity to achieve peace with the Palestinians,'' said
Tazli Reshef, a leader of Peace Now.
   Arguments broke out with right-wing counter-demonstrators, and
Israel radio said five right-wingers were arrested for disturbing
the march.
   Shamir has repeatedly rejected an international conference,
saying it would resu lt in other countries ganging up on Israel and
forcing it to yield land that Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc
maintains is an inextricable part of Israel.
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres of the Labor Party, Shamir's rival
in the coalition government, supports an international conference
and territorial concessions. He said Israel had to take the lead in
peacemaking or suffer a further loss of support in the United
States.
   ``It's clear we have real losses in U.S. public opinion, and the
American public opinion is one of our most important political
assets,'' he said on Israel army radio.
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens, a close Shamir ally, said in a
radio interview he did not expect American pressure to change
Shamir's opposition to talks with the PLO or the establishment of
an independent Palestinian state.
   Yossi Ben Aharon, Shamir's chief of staff, indicated Shamir was
willing to listen to U.S. proposals for easing tensions in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, such as freeing some of about 5,000
Palestinians held in Israeli jails.
   ``We have no problem with such measures as long as they are not
one-sided, which would compound the problem and give the impression
we were knuckling under to pressure,'' he said.
   On the other hand, Ben Aharon said in an interview, ``we don't
need sermons'' on the conduct of Israeli soldiers.
   Ben Aharon said Shamir was taking with him some new ideas ``but
not a blueprint'' for Middle East peace. He stressed that while
Israel was willing to be flexible on some points it would not
accept even an indirect dialogue with the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Among the proposals is one for elections in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip to choose Palestinian representatives for
negotiations with Israel on autonomy for the 1.7 million Arabs.
   However, prominent Palestinians said in interviews the election
proposal would be unacceptable as long as Israel refused to commit
itself to ending the occupation and declined to deal with the PLO
or accept a Palestinian state.
   ``We know that Shamir who was an obstructionist throughout his
life cannot deliver any of these things,'' said Saeb Erakat, a
political science professor at An Najah University in the West Bank.
   ``He will take old ideas in new cans, under new labels,'' said
Erakat, who predicted there would be a new flareup in the nearly
16-month-old uprising if progress was not made soon in peace
efforts.
   Hanna Siniora, editor of the pro-PLO daily Al Fajr newspaper,
said Palestinians would not agree to elections unless Israel
withdrew its troops and turned over control to U.N. peacekeeping
forces.
</TEXT>
