<FIRST>r a AM-PornographyMistake     04-03 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pornography Mistake,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Officials Mistake Pet Reproduction For Animal Attraction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attempt by an advertising agency to ship
videotapes called ``Sex Talk'' and ``Tiger'' to the Cannes Film
Festival prompted British officials to bar them as pornography.
   In fact, the tapes were television ads prepared for the
Massachusetts Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals
encouraging pet owners to neuter their dogs and cats.
   But customs officers at London's Heathrow International Airport
mistook the messages on pet reproduction for films of animal
attraction, a spokeswoman for the ad agency said Monday.
   Regina Ryan of Cosmopulous, Crowley &amp; Daly, said the tapes and
two others were intercepted March 16 on their way to the
international film festival in Cannes, France, which is later in
the spring.
   The festival awards prizes and has a category for public service
announcements, Ms. Ryan said. Entry rules require each submission
to have the name of the piece and its length clearly marked on the
package.
   The other spots were Liberty Mutual Insurance Co.'s ``Buried
Treasure'' about the risk of drunk driving, and the Salvation
Army's ``Places to Eat,'' about hunger and homelessness. But
British Customs evidently took one look at the ``Sex Talk'' label
and decided to send it all back where it came from.
   An agent in London notified the Cosmopulous agency and
repackaged tapes stating their destination were sent just in time
for Cannes' March 18 deadline, Ms. Ryan said.
   ``After all this, I hope we win,'' she said.
</TEXT>
