<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador     04-03 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Revokes Order Freeing Alleged Kidnappers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Monday revoked his
predecessor's order for the release of three alleged members of a
kidnapping ring involving military officers.
   Judge Ricardo Mejia Angulo of the 3rd Criminal Court told
journalists he voided a ruling issued Friday afternoon by Judge
Hector Larios. Mejia Angulo's action, which included a new order
for the provisional detention of the three, began to calm outrage
vented following Larios' surprise order.
   ``The genie is back in the bottle,'' a high-ranking U.S.
diplomat said in an interview. The United States, which provides El
Salvador about $1.5 million a day in aid, was upset by Larios'
order.
   Washington considers prosecution of the kidnapping ring case a
top priority in establishing a viable judicial system in this
country.
   The kidnappers, masquerading as leftist guerrillas, abducted
five wealthy businessmen for ransom between 1980 and 1985.
   Larios, minutes before leaving his post as the head of the 3rd
Criminal Court, ruled that Maj. Alfredo Jimenez Moreno, former Lt.
Rodolfo Lopez Sibrian and wealthy farmer Orlando Llovera Balette
should be released.
   President-elect Alfredo Cristiani of the rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance party, or Arena, is to meet Friday in
Washington with President Bush.
   Diplomatic sources said Cristiani called U.S. Ambassador William
Walker late Friday to inform him of Larios' order. Cristiani, who
won the March 19 presidential election by a wide margin over the
candidate of the incumbent Christian Democrats, was described as
incensed by Larios' move.
   Some Arena leaders, including cashiered army Maj. Roberto
d'Aubuisson, have been linked to death squads and other rights
abuses in the early 1980s.
   Llovera, Lopez Sibrian and Jimenez, as well as others implicated
in the kidnapping ring, are former friends and associates of
d'Aubuisson, who is an Arena legislator.
   The U.S. source, who commented on condition of anonymity, said
the case was Cristiani's first human rights test as president-elect.
   ``He passed with flying colors,'' said the diplomat.
   Jose Guerrero, president of the Supreme Court, told journalists
that Larios, who transferred to a Civil Court post Monday, has been
suspended pending investigation of his ruling regarding the alleged
kidnappers.
   Larios had ruled that the three had been arrested in 1986 under
emergency legislation no longer in effect, making their detentions
illegal.
   Only Llovera was released. His whereabouts were unknown Monday.
The release order concerning the other two men was not implemented
before Mejia Angulo's action.
   The judge also issued new arrest warrants, replacing those
cancelled by Larios, for five other people allegedly involved in
the ring.
   The ring, in which at least two fugitive military officers are
implicated, was broken in 1986, when Llovera, Jimenez and Lopez
Sibrian were arrested.
   Lopez Sibrian was expelled from the armed forces. Jimenez
remains in the army, though under arrest.
   The case has not gone to trial.
</TEXT>
