<HEAD>Plane Crashes on Edge of City, Former General Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A single-engine plane crashed on the
eastern edge of the capital Monday, killing all three people on
board and injuring three on the ground, aviation officials said.
   Among those killed was the pilot, retired Gen. Luis Federico
Fuentes Corado, 53, who was assistant defense minister in the
mid-1970s.
   It was not clear why the plane crashed. It headed back to Aurora
International Airport about 15 minutes after taking off for Puerto
Barrios, on the Caribbean coast, but crashed into a house under
construction, said Julio Cesar Motta, assistant civil aviation
director.
   Also killed were a photographer and an engineer. They planned to
take aerial photographs of ranches near Puerto Barrios, 185 miles
northeast of Guatemala City, according to the owner of an aerial
photography company that chartered the plane.
   The three injured were construction workers at the house.
   After serving as defense minister, Fuentes Corado was ambassador
to El Salvador and was director of the National Reconstruction
Committee under military governments in the early 1980s.
