<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 2244EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-B-1BGroundingLifted     04-03 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-B-1B Grounding Lifted,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>B-1B Bomber Fleet Cleared for Takeoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Strategic Air Command ordered the
nation's B-1B bomber fleet back into the air, nearly a week after a
mechanical glitch was discovered in one plane, an Air Force
spokesman said.
   All 97 planes were returned to active status in an order
received by B-1B bases Sunday evening, said Lt. Col. Paul Muehring,
chief of public affairs for McConnell Air Force Base in Wichita,
where 16 of the bombers are based.
   The order by Gen. John Chain Jr., SAC commander-in-chief, was
based on inspections that began shortly after the planes were
grounded last Tuesday.
   A Strategic Air Command spokesman, Capt. Harry Edwards of Offutt
Air Force Base, Neb., said two planes passed inspection and flew
from McConnell Air Force Base Monday. But although some of the
B-1Bs were again operating, the order was not a blanket approval
for the entire B-1B fleet to return immediately to the air, he said.
   ``Each aircraft will be returned to flying status upon
completion of the inspection and correction of any deficiencies,''
Edwards said. ``We do have some flying.''
   The grounding was a result of a problem discovered last Monday
during a pre-flight check of a B-1B at Dyess Air Force Base in
Texas. It was the third time the multimillion-dollar planes have
been grounded in the past 18 months.
   The B-1B's wings, which can move from a forward position to a
swept-back position, did not appear to be working in
synchronization with each other. A mechanic disconnected a switch
to investigate the problem, but that disabled the mechanism that
prevented the wing from going past the forward limit.
   One wing moved a few inches too far forward and punctured a fuel
tank, Muehring said.
   After the problem developed, 25 B-1Bs were spot-checked at six
bases, including two of McConnell's planes. No problems were
discovered, Muehring said.
   A second order was issued later in the week to check all 97
planes in the fleet, Muehring said, and inspections continued
through the weekend.
</TEXT>
