<FIRST>r a AM-GrocerKilled     04-03 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grocer Killed,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Call Slaying of Anti-Drug Crusader a Paid Hit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Monday called the slaying of an anti-drug
crusader a contract hit, and said they are seeking three men who
allegedly ordered the killing last month.
   Two men were arrested Sunday on first-degree murder charges for
the shooting death of Lee Arthur Lawrence, the owner of a small
grocery store who was unflagging in his efforts to rid his
neighborhood of drugs.
   Lawrence, 51, was killed in a fusillade of up to 30 bullets
March 20 outside his store in Perrine, an impoverished community
about 10 miles south of Miami.
   The two men arrested Sunday were identified as Ronnie Johnson
and Rodney Newsome, both 21. In addition to the murder charges,
they face attempted murder counts for wounding two men who were in
Lawrence's grocery store during the shooting.
   Fred Taylor, head of the Metro-Dade police force, said the
amount of money and the motives for the crime could not be revealed
immediately.
   ``I'm afraid that some of the speculation will continue in the
case until we know why and who and where the death was ordered
from,'' he said. ``We feel we have those who did the shooting in
this case.''
   Information helping to break the case was phoned to a police tip
line, he said.
   In addition to Lawrence's death, Johnson was charged with the
mid-March killing of a reputed drug dealer in Perrine, and the
attempted murder of a Perrine man on March 5, police spokeswoman
Myriam Royle said.
   Also on Monday, the county began tearing down crack houses only
a few blocks from the site where Lawrence was killed.
   ``The neighbors are very happy that we're taking these houses
down because of the activities that go on at night,'' said Dade
County Commissioner Larry Hawkins. ``They feel unsafe.''
   The parking lot next to Lawrence's store was the scene of
frequent drug transactions and the market was the target of a
failed fire-bombing attempt in 1987. A week before the shooting,
Lawrence reported the latest in a series of death threats that
began in late 1986.
   More than 800 mourners, including President Bush's son Jeb,
attended Lawrence's funeral. President and Mrs. Bush sent
condolences to his family.
</TEXT>
