<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv04   04-03 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv04,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tuesday, April 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>How To Be The Death of The Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Bu JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You might be able to get a fairly accurate view
of what's ahead for the economy if you simply interview your
friends or neighbors at the next social event you attend.
   While it won't make you the life of the party, and conceivably
could kill it, such interviews might provide you with a fair
picture of future interest rates, jobs, inflation and even the
gross national product.
   You must accept whatever social consequences ensue, but isn't
that a fair enough price for a look into the mysterious future?
   The suggestion arises from evidence that consumers en masse are
pretty good at forecasting the economic future and even at making
the proper moves in anticipation of developments.
   Consumers are so good at this, in fact, that the Department of
Commerce recently announced the Index of Consumer Expectations
derived from studies at the University of Michigan will be included
among its leading, or advance, indicators.
   While your informal survey will be informative, it won't, of
course, carry the authoritativeness of the Michigan survey, which
is scientifically construed and professionally analyzed and has a
track record dating to 1946.
   In that time, consumer expectations have foretold by weeks and
months the movement of several significant economic measures. There
is no magic to it; perhaps instinct plays a large role, and
self-concern too.
   Consider these factors:
   1. Most consumers are not mere robots who automatically grab the
lure of advertisers. They do have minds and sometimes they use them.
   2. When it concerns their own money, most consumers have a high
sense of fiduciary responsibility.
   3. This a consumer economy. Consumers account for more getting
and spending than business or government. Taken as a whole,
consumers are a vast economic power that can dictate economic
changes when perceptions are acted out.
   Richard Curtin, director of Michigan's Survey Research Center,
states that consumer expectations change, on average, two quarters
in advance of movements in the prime interest rate, three quarters
in advance of changes in the jobless rate and one quarter in
advance of changes in the consumer price index.
   Moreover, he says, the subjective assessments of consumers in
regard to current business conditions usually are documented by the
official statistics, which aren't released until weeks and months
later.
   In the latest reading of the consumer mind, financial prospects
for the year ahead were considered quite favorably. The majority
expected good times financially in the economy as a whole.
   Unemployment was expected to remain unchanged at its very low
levels, but a record number of consumers expected interest rates to
rise. Inflation was foreseen averaging 4.8 percent, or not much
different from the existing rate.
   You may, if you choose, conduct your own test among neighbors,
friends and relatives, but a couple of caveats should be observed.
   You should be aware that the larger the group the more
representative it is likely to be. Individuals might be overly
optimistic or pessimistic; what is important is aggregate opinion
and objective analysis of the results.
   The second caveat is that should you actually attempt such a
survey at a socialt you must assume full responsibility for
the consequences.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues., April 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
