<DOCNO> AP890403-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1359EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-Warsaw'sOldBristol Adv10   04-03 0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warsaw's Old Bristol, Adv 10,0865</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, April 10, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Poles Trying to Restore Old Elegance of Warsaw's Hotel Bristol</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is easier to see the present's failure
than the past's legendary elegance in what remains of the Hotel
Bristol.
   And it is hard for people of Warsaw today to believe that the
Bristol will ever reopen, its scaffolded facade and stripped
interior having stood for so long as a nagging reminder of Poland's
dismal economic slide.
   Even now, as workers shoulder sacks of cement through its doors
and decorators slip bits of pink brocade onto blueprints, there is
rampant skepticism that the communist government can carry off its
grand plans to recapture the days when the pianist Ignacy
Paderewski commanded a block-long suite and tipsy guests tripped
carefree through the garden fountain.
   But government-backed renovators, who have been at work 18
months, say will recreate a first-class hotel on deadline, Sept.
25, 1991.
   ``It has been too long that this hotel has had its magnificence
taken away,'' said Krzysztof Wojcik, director of the Investment
Realization Board of ORBIS, the national tourism company.
   The government has allotted 18 billion zlotys ($31.5 million at
the official exchange or $6 million at the black market rate) for
the Bristol.
   Once among Europe's most elegant hotels with silver settings
that included four pieces just for eating crayfish, it was much in
decline even from its postwar incarnation with a ``people's
tavern'' when it closed for renovations in 1980.
   The martial-law crackdown on the independent Solidarity union
movement in 1981 intervened. Western loans and investments were cut
off and Poland's staggering economy had no room for the project.
   About 1.5 million zlotys have been spent so far to pare the
block-square, eight-story hotel down to brick and beam and to begin
to install new services.
   Although built at the turn of the century with all the modern
techniques and conveniences of the time, the difficulty of
``installing the technology of the 20th century into these old
walls'' also has slowed the work, said Tadeusz Jarecki, a
renovation coordinator.
   Just how sumptuous the Bristol will be depends on the special
team of designers charged with recapturing the Viennese art-nouveau
style of its first decades and how much the elements imported from
the West cost in precious hard currency.
   ``We also hope that there will be some interest shown (by
investors) on the American side,'' said director Wojcik. ``We all
know America, rich and beautiful as it is, lacks the historical
monuments we have in Europe.''
   Renovators say they plan to restore the hotel's marble stairs,
mirrors, chandeliers, furniture and even Paderewski's piano.
   Design schemes call a grand entrance with a brass crest in a
granite sidewalk. The Raspberry Room restaurant will be recreated
in pink and gilt and each floor of the 344-bed hotel will be color
coordinated down to the chambermaids' uniform.
   Now, however, there are few walls, no doors and much rubble. In
the courtyard where a glass conservatory once glittered are piles
of pipes and boards dumped unceremoniously over the years in what
one project director called ``a socialist hell.''
   Built by Paderewski's investment company, the Bristol flourished
between the two world wars, when he served briefly as premier.
   The guest register was studded with notables from the world of
diplomacy, finance, the arts and aristocracy. Hollywood's famous
couple, Mary Pickford and Douglas Fairbanks, surveyed the
tree-lined boulevard from their balcony in 1926 and the renovators
hope their names and others will hang from a ``visiting card tree''
in the lobby of the new Bristol.
   The Nazi occupiers took the hotel over during World War II.
   The Bristol was one of the few buildings in the city's historic
center still standing when the Soviet Red Army entered Warsaw in
January 1945.
   On Josef V. Stalin's birthday in 1949, the ``People's Tavern''
opened at the Bristol and the Russian-Polish menu instructed
customers that ``tipping offends the dignity of the working man.''
   ORBIS took over in 1952, redecorating and modernizing. Many
dignitaries still took rooms, including Sen. John F. Kennedy, who
needed a special bed board because of back problems during his 1959
stay.
   It remained the smartest hotel in Warsaw through the 1960s. But
even the official history acknowledges that no repairs were made
after 1952 and the Bristol was being used as a dormitory for
students when it closed.
   To this day, however, the Bristol is warmly remembered by many
Poles as a bright spot in an often-bleak postwar period. They
recall animated debates around the cafe's tables as students from
nearby Warsaw University and festive evenings out at the Column
Room restaurant.
   ``As with everyone living in Warsaw, I have personal memories,''
said Wojcik. ``My sister was working in this hotel for 25 years
until it was closed. That is why I have a deep personal and
professional conviction to have this hotel restored.''
   And so Warsaw is waiting.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 10</NOTE>
</DOC>
