<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1341EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--Ethics Adv16-1stAdd   04-03 1006</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Ethics, Adv 16-1st Add,1027</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDATED: to do.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Since the early days of the Vietnam War, most daily headlines
and leading items on the TV evening news have involved moral as
well as legal choices: The Pentagon papers. The Watergate break-in.
The village of My Lai. Pulling the plug on Karen Ann Quinlan. Lust
and greed among TV evangelists. Oliver North, hero or villain?
   Lt. Col. North argues he lied to Congress to serve a higher
good. Socrates defied the law in refusing to finger fellow
Athenians opposed to the rule of the 30 Tyrants. From jail cells,
Henry Thoreau and Martin Luther King urged disobedience to unjust
laws. Jeb Magruder said his role model for breaking the law in the
Watergate affair was his old ethics teacher at Yale, the Rev.
William Sloane Coffin, who ``recommended that students burn their
draft cards, shut down the city of Washington.''
   On ``house calls'' to industry, ethicist Newton shies from the
designation philosopher: ``That's someone who stands around the
water cooler all day,'' she says.'' A cartoon on her office door
comes closer to describing the role of the ethicist in industry. A
harried executive is pushing a button on the intercom and intoning:
``Miss Wattles, will you send someone in who knows right from
wrong.''
   Lately, leaders in the fields of government, medicine, law,
engineering, computers, journalism have been pushing the button for
an expert consultant to help write some ethical guidelines or deal
with cases of misconduct.
   A recent example of job opportunities for a latter-day Socrates
is the nationwide search conducted by Florida's Poynter Institute
for a theologian or philosopher to head up its Ethics Center. Three
other branches of this highly respected institute concentrate on
improving skills and standards of working journalists in writing,
graphics and management.
   ``We believe people at every level can be trained to think about
ethical dilemmas,'' says institute president Robert Haiman. ``So
when that big call comes up at 10:40 and you're going to press at
11, you have a more orderly way to approach it.
   ``A lot of these ethical calls have to be made by street
reporters. We're talking about reportorial behavior. Is it OK to
read upside down on somebody's desk? Is it OK to open a guy's file
cabinet while he's out of the office? Is it OK to lie about who you
are, to pretend you're an ambulance attendant or whatever?''
   Some at the top of the executive ladder argue that ethics
training should begin at the very bottom, long before college or
professional school.
   ``If an MBA candidate doesn't know the difference between
honesty and crime, between lying and telling the truth,'' wrote IBM
Chairman John Akers in a recent issue of the Sloane Management
Review, ``then business school, in all probability, will not
produce a convert.''
   Akers finds it ``ludicrous that even divinity schools and law
schools and departments of philosophy have to pay proctors to pad
up and down the aisles at examination time to make sure nobody is
looking at crib notes or copying from a neighbor.''
   An increasing number of Fortune 500 companies and countless
smaller firms are calling in experts to help draft a formal code of
ethics.
   Chemical Bank's ``Code of Ethics,'' which must be read and
signed by all its 30,000 employees worldwide, is among the most
widely copied. To translate the code into an ``operating
philosophy,'' more than 250 vice presidents have undergone a
two-day seminar on ``decision making and corporate values,''
presided over by the bank's chairman.
   The code is credited with Chemical's decision to create a
special lending unit for minority businesses and its refusal to
finance arms exporters and corporate raiders, or do business with
pornographers, massage parlors, and several countries run by
dictators.
   Chief executive officer James Burke calls Johnson and Johnson's
``credo,'' which dates back to 1945, ``the glue'' that held the
health care multinational together during two nightmare Tylenol
poisoning incidents and played ``the most important role'' in
withdrawing the capsules.
   The credo also dictated management's decision to stop
advertising their baby oil as a tanning lotion after medical
evidence showed the product speeded up the sun's harming effects on
the skin. Sales immediately plunged from $10 million to $5 million,
but again the firm bounced back.
   Why are ethics suddenly hot now?
   In the wake of the scandals in Wall Street, Chicago's commodity
market and defense contracts, there is an awareness that the
company which acts responsibly can avoid fines and jail sentences,
reduce court suits that entail costly legal and accounting fees,
diminish the threat of more government regulation, increase company
morale and attract a higher type, more loyal employee.
   ``There is a growing conviction that strong corporate culture
and ethics are a vital strategic key to survival and profitability
in a highly competitive era,'' concludes The Business Roundtable, a
public issues forum for some 200 top chief executive officers,
after an in-depth study of the corporate ethics of 10 leading
firms, including Boeing, Chemical Bank, General Mills and Xerox.
   A few weeks ago, New York's Harvard Club witnessed an unlikely
gathering of theologians, philosophers and Wall Street brokers and
analysts to launch ``Ethics in the Financial Marketplace,'' by John
Casey, managing director of the investment firm Scudder, Stevens
and Clark.
   When Casey, a disciple of Chuck Powers, sat down at his Apple II
word processor to write a ``how-to'' guide to responsible business
behavior, friends on Wall Street joked that it would be ``one of
the shortest books ever written.''
   The Rev. Langan, who never disguises the fact he is a Jesuit
priest when going into a firm, notes that the Yuppie philosophy of
grab it all quick any which way is somewhat in decline.
   ``Some of the fast-trackers are more cautious now that the
market is less giddy,'' he says. ``Also, when you see people barred
for life from the security industry, it gives pause to think.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 16</NOTE>
