<HEAD>Eurotunnel Says Opening Pushed Back One Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anglo-French consortium Eurotunnel said Monday
that it pushed back by one month the completion of its 31-mile
underwater rail link between Britain and France amid escalating
expenses.
   The opening is to take place June 15, 1993 instead of May 15 of
that year, the company said following negotiations with the
construction companies working on the project.
   Eurotunnel also disclosed that its expenses, after investment
income, rose to $926 million in 1988 from $652 million a year
earlier. By the end of 1988, total costs, after investment income,
for the three years of operation were $1.7 billion.
