<FIRST>r f PM-Carson-Bergner     04-03 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carson-Bergner,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bergner Offers $282 Million For Carson Pirie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Department store chain Carson Pirie Scott &amp; Co.
says its board of directors will review a $282 million takeover bid
from competitor P.A. Bergner &amp; Co. but it already has cast doubts
on the likelihood of a merger.
   Carson spokeswoman Kate Leatham declined to comment Sunday on
whether the $20-per-share cash takeover bid was welcome. But in a
statement, Carson characterized the proposal as ``unsolicited,
highly conditional (and) ambiguous.''
   Ms. Leatham said the proposal was received late Friday
afternoon. She said the board will consider the bid but that a
board meeting had not yet been set. According to the Carson
statement, Bergner offered at least $20 per share in cash for
Carson, or, alternatively, offered to acquire only Carson's
department store division for ``an unspecified combination of cash,
stock and notes.''
   Bergner spokesman Jerry Seeman said the company had retained
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and Financo as its advisers for the
proposal and had been assured by its commercial bank of funding for
a possible acquisition.
   The offer appears to clash with several recent moves announced
by Carson Chairman Peter Willmott.
   Last month, Willmott said Carson planned to sell its catalog
operation and close its Corporate Level specialty store in
Washington D.C. as part of a restructuring program begun in 1987.
   Carson's department store business consists of 33 stores in the
Chicago area and in Minnesota. The company also owns County Seat, a
jeans and casual-clothing specialty chain with about 400 stores.
   Carson reported revenues of $1.02 billion and a net loss of $38
million _ much of it resulting from the catalog operation _ for
fiscal 1988.
   Bergner operates 31 department stores in Illinois and Wisconsin.
Seeman said the company reported revenues of $470 million last
year, but added that a profit or loss figure was not available
immediately.
   Bergner is owned by the Maus and Nordmann families, Swiss
nationals who operate 70 department stores in Switzerland and the
well-known Au Printemps department store in Paris.
</TEXT>
