<SECOND>PM-MCA-Sony,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sony Denies Talks Under Way with Sony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sony Corp. denied reports today that the
Japanese electronics company was negotiating to buy MCA Inc., the
entertainment conglomerate that owns Universal Studios.
   ``That's a rumor,'' said Jason Farrell, vice president for
corporate communications at Sony's offices in New Jersey. ``Sony is
not negotiating with MCA.''
   Los Angeles radio station KNX-AM reported on Friday that a deal
for Sony to buy MCA would be announced today.
   But Farrell, asked if an announcement was forthcoming, told a
reporter, ``You know better.''
   MCA President Sidney Sheinberg has refused to comment on the KNX
report, which came on the heels of an announcement that the film
studio United Artists was being sold for $1 billion to
Australian-based Qintex Group.
   MCA, based in Universal City, Calif., is worth an estimated $5.5
billion.
   Securities analysts have said for some time that Sony was
interested in buying a U.S. movie company. The Japanese company
moved into the American entertainment industry last year with the
purchase of CBS records.
   Qintex owns an Australian TV network but is best known in the
United States as one of the makers of the CBS miniseries ``Lonesome
Dove.'' The company would get the United Artists moviemaking group
and its 4,000-film library, including the James Bond, Rocky and
Pink Panther movies, and the Oscar-winning ``Rain Man.''
</TEXT>
