<DOCNO> AP890403-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1106EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AutoIncentives     04-03 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Incentives,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chrysler Announces `No More Mr. Nice Guy'' Financing: Free Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. plunged into a new automaker
incentive battle today with interest-free loans, undercutting 2.9
percent financing deals offered last week by its two big U.S.
rivals because of slow sales.
   The No. 3 automaker's ``No More Mr. Nice Guy'' program, gives
free financing on two-year loans for 1988- and 1989-model cars and
some trucks. The rates for longer loans range from 5.9 percent to
10.9 percent. No expiration date for the program was set.
   ``It can't get any lower,'' Chrysler Motors Chairman Bennett E.
Bidwell said. ``It can't get any simpler. It can't get any better
for the customer.''
   The zero percent financing program covers all Chrysler's 1988
and 1989 cars, 99 percent of its trucks and about 25 percent of its
hot-selling Jeep models.
   Ford Motor Co. started the latest wave Wednesday with a plan
featuring 2.9 percent interest rates on two-year loans. General
Motors Corp. followed a day later, basically matching Ford's move.
   It's the first time in nearly two years that the Big Three have
brawled so aggressively with cheap financing for cars, reflecting
their fear of a consumer buying slowdown that could create huge
backlogs of unsold 1989 models.
   Ford's vice president for North American sales, Robert Rewey,
acknowledged last Wednesday that part of the motivation for the No.
2 automaker's move into heavier incentives was because early 1989
sales have been below expectations.
   Low-financing or cash rebate incentives, when they're working,
can shrink automakers' inventories, make serious buyers out of
casual lookers and give the industry a shot in the arm during
sagging sales periods.
   When they don't work, they can eat profits and put an unwelcome
burden on dealers.'
   Automakers are betting that incentives will provide the boost
the industry needs to get back on track during the normally busy
early spring period.
   The new incentive programs from Ford and GM also make four-year
financing more attractive by reducing the interest rate from 8.9
percent to 6.9 percent.
   Car and truck sales during the middle 10 days of March were up 5
percent over the same period of 1988, but down 5.3 percent for the
first 20 days of the month and down 5.4 percent since Jan. 1.
   Sales figures for all of March are due Tuesday.
   Some analysts have been revising their earnings projections for
the automakers this year. One reason is slower sales and another is
the costly incentives designed to raise sales in the first place.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
