<HEAD>Young President Named at Columbia Records</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Records announced Monday that Don Ienner has
been named president of Columbia Records on Monday, becoming at age
36 the youngest executive ever to head the record label.
   The announcement was made by Tommy Mottola, president of the CBS
Records Division, which oversees Columbia Records.
   CBS Records is a unit of Sony Corp. of Japan.
   Most recently, Ienner has been executive vice president and
general manager of Arista Records. He was closely associated with
the launching of Whitney Houston at Arista, which he joined in 1983
as vice president of promotion.
   Ienner started his career while in high school, working in the
Capitol Records mailroom in 1969. From 1972 through 1977 he was in
partnership with his brother Jimmy Ienner in a publishing,
management and production company. He went to Arista from
Millennium Records, a label he co-founded in 1977.
