<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1809EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Sony-MCA     04-03 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sony-MCA,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rumor Reports Subside On Sony-MCA</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Foreign Invasion Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of MCA Inc. common stock climbed
Monday despite Sony Corp.'s denial of a report that it was
negotiating to acquire the entertainment giant.
   ``Sony is not negotiating with MCA.'' said Jason Farrow, vice
president for corporate communications at Sony's offices in New
Jersey.
   MCA President Sidney Sheinberg has called the report a rumor.
   Nonetheless, MCA gained $3.87{ a share to $56.62{ in trading
Monday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Analysts said Sony and MCA were likely candidates for talks.
   ``I think there's a relatively low probability (of a merger). I
think that they have probably spoken to each other, like Sony has
spoken to many, many people on the street,'' said Harold Vogel,
entertainment industry analyst for Merrill Lynch Pierce, Fenner &amp;
Smith Inc. ``My best guess is that there will be nothing
happening.''
   Chris Jones of the investment firm Bateman Eichler, Hill
Richards in Los Angeles said MCA and Sony were likely candidates
for talks, but warned that Sony could have many interests in the
MCA conglomerate, which includes movies, music, entertainment
parks, books and licensing.
   But the Sony style, Jones noted, has been to move carefully.
   ``I can tell you that their strategy has been one of building
relationships with companies,'' she said. ``They had a 20-year
relationship with CBS before they acquired their music catalogue.''
   ``They are very methodical _ slow. They are constantly
reevaluating and have historically worked from long-term
relationships in making acquisitions,'' she said.
   Her firm estimates MCA is worth just over $5 billion and well
positioned as a major force in the entertainment industry.
   Meanwhile, Los Angeles' KNX-AM Newsradio stood by its story of
Friday that said a deal was in the works between the two corporate
giants.
   One aspect of any merger would be the likely need for the
combination to dispense with MCA's huge music catalog to avoid
antitrust problems. Sony already owns CBS Records, with such
artists as Bruce Springsteen and Michael Jackson, and its huge
library of recordings.
   The MCA catalog includes some of the best-known artists in 20th
century American music, including Duke Ellington, Count Basie,
Woody Herman, the Ink Spots, the Mills Brothers, Judy Garland,
Patsy Cline, B.B. King and Buddy Holly. There is also the entire
Chess records rhythm and blues catalog, including Chuck Berry, Bo
Diddley, Muddy Waters and Howlin' Wolf.
   Modern artists include Elton John, Tiffany, The Boys, New
Edition, and country stars Reba McEntire, George Strait, Lyle
Lovett, Lacy J. Dalton and the Bellamy Brothers.
</TEXT>
