<FIRST>r f BC-Thomson-MedicalJournals     04-03 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Thomson-Medical Journals,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Thomson To Buy Medical Journals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Thomson Organization said Monday it
would add to its media empire by acquiring the publisher of a group
of Canadian medical journals.
   International Thomson said Monday it will pay 8.5 million
Canadian dollars for the publishing arm of Trimel Corp., a Toronto
firm that provides services to the pharmaceutical industry. Trimel
shareholders still have to approve the deal at a meeting April 28.
   Thomson, which has proposed to merge with Thomson Newspapers
Ltd. to form a multi-billion-dollar media giant under the name
Thomson Corp., controls more than 100 magazines and 70 newspapers.
   In announcing the merger plan last month, Ken Thomson, chairman
of both organizations, said the new company would focus on
acquiring new publishing companies.
   Alan Lewis, treasurer for International Thomson, said the Trimel
deal was in the works before the announcement.
   Trimel produces such publications as Drug Protocol, Pharmacy
Practice and Today's Health.
   The company also operates an electronic information network for
doctors that is not part of the deal.
   Company president Eugene Melnyk said Trimel is selling its
publications to concentrate on electronic services and on its
pharmaceutical business, Galen Pharma.
</TEXT>
