<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 1854EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TankerSpill-Arco     04-03 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill-Arco,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arco Says Delivery Schedules Imperiled by Alaska Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil customers of the Atlantic Richfield
Co. were warned Monday that delivery schedules for Alaskan crude
might be delayed because the massive oil spill off Valdez has
slowed tanker shipments.
   ``What we are telling our customers now is we can't meet every
requirement in their contract,'' Arco spokesman Albert Greenstein
said. Vessel delays at the Port of Valdez were blamed.
   Customers were told Friday that deliveries may be pro-rated in
the near future, ``but we are not at that point yet,'' said
Greenstein. Arco sells 50,000 to 70,000 barrels a day of Alaskan
crude oil.
   Arco's share of North Slope oil is about 520,000 barrels daily,
most of that processed in its own refineries.
   Earlier last week, British Petroleum's BP America Inc. and the
Exxon Corp. said they had temporarily halted April Alaskan crude
oil contracts.
   On Monday, Exxon apologized for causing the nation's biggest oil
spill and promised to clean up every fouled beach in Prince William
Sound, but workers on those greasy-smelling beaches said their
efforts were futile.
   The tanker Exxon Valdez crashed into Bligh Reef on March 24,
spilling 10.1 million gallons of North Slope crude. The oil slick
has now grown larger than Rhode Island, the nation's smallest state
at 1,214 square miles.
</TEXT>
