<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 2109EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ForbesList     04-03 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Forbes List,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Heads Forbes List Of Most Valuable Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. was the
most valuable company in the United States in 1988 for a fifth
straight year, Forbes Magazine plans to report in its May 1 issue.
   The world's largest computer company was worth $71.8 billion at
the end of 1988, going by the price of a share times the number of
shares outstanding, Forbes said Monday.
   IBM grabbed the top spot in 1984 after American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co. fell off because of the breakup of the Bell System.
   The top five companies kept their positions last year. The
companies making the biggest jumps among the top 10 were Ford Motor
Co., which rose to sixth from ninth, and Du Pont Co., which fell to
ninth from sixth.
   The top 10 companies in market value were:
   1. International Business Machines Corp., $71.8 billion, up 4.2
percent from 1987.
   2. Exxon Corp., $56.7 billion, up 7.9 percent.
   3. General Electric Co., $40.4 billion, up 1.3 percent.
   4. American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., $30.87 billion, up 6.5
percent.
   5. General Motors Corp., $30.85 billion, 25.3 percent.
   6. Ford Motor Co., $24.1 billion, up 29.7 percent.
   7. Philip Morris Cos. Inc., $23.5 billion, up 16.5 percent.
   8. Merck &amp; Co. Inc., $22.9 billion, up 10.1 percent.
   9. Du Pont Co., $21.1 billion, up 1.3 percent.
   10. Amoco Corp., $19.4 billion, up 9.1 percent.
</TEXT>
