<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-89 2159EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-C&amp;S-NCNB 1stLd-Writethru f0274 04-03 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-C&amp;S-NCNB, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0274,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>C&amp;S Board Opposes NCNB Buyout Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf pvs, ``It was ...,'' to UPDATE
with NCNB statement on C&amp;S's comments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Citizens and Southern Corp., parent
corporation of Georgia's C&amp;S Bank, announced Monday that its board
has decided to fight an uninvited takeover attempt by the giant
NCNB Corp. which would create the nation's sixth-largest banking
concern.
   The Atlanta-based bank holding company, in a statement, termed
the NCNB stock swap offer ``inadequate,'' and said C&amp;S' present
management is better able to serve the bank's customers,
shareholders and communities than NCNB.
   ``We have managed this bank for service, growth, profitability
and long-term service to shareholders _ not for a quick sale,'' C&amp;S
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Bennett A. Brown said. ``The
board of directors and the management have concluded that this
offer is clearly inadequate and not in the best interests of C&amp;S
shareholders, customers and employees.''
   NCNB, the Southeast's largest banking company, surprised C&amp;S
late last Thursday with a $2.4 billion stock offer for the
Atlanta-based bank. C&amp;S management was cool to the idea from the
start.
   ``It was unsolicited,'' said C&amp;S Chief Financial Officer James
D. Dixon. ``It was uninvited.''
   In a statement Monday night, NCNB Corp. called its offer ``fair
and generous'' and said its legal advisers felt there is no
regulatory block to such an acquisition.
   ``We are determined to proceed, and request the C&amp;S Board to
reconsider our offer and promptly authorize negotiations,'' the
release said.
   In its official offer, NCNB had told C&amp;S it wanted to begin
``active merger discussions'' within five business days. That now
is unlikely to happen.
   C&amp;S' board, in addition to voting unanimously to reject the NCNB
offer, also decided in its meeting Monday to adopt a new article in
the corporation's bylaws, under Georgia's Business Combination Act,
preventing any major shareholders from combining with the
corporation for five years, unless certain conditions are met.
   The bid for C&amp;S followed a highly publicized push by the
Charlotte, N.C.-based NCNB into Texas last year, buying into the
Republic Bank Corp. of Dallas. A combined NCNB and C&amp;S would create
a formidable bank with $76 billion in assets. NCNB officials
characterized their buyout offer as a friendly one, and vowed to
leave C&amp;S' managers _ and its name _ in place in Georgia.
   Under NCNB's plan, each C&amp;S shareholder would bet 1.075 shares
of NCNB common stock for each of their C&amp;S shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
